@NODE "Mail_3" "Re: 060 and Blitz"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    15 Dec 98 12:17:42 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Tue, 15 Dec 1998 12:17:38 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: 060 and Blitz

On 15 Dec 98, at 5:50, Curt Esser wrote:

> > It seems, you've got one. First try two small things. 1) Put a Forbid_
> > before the End, it often crashes an 060. 

 Wasn't the original problem with compiling, in that it crashed at the sta=
rt, 
not when it had run, or even when it got to the end of the program. Crashe=
d 
with empty sources files as well didn't it?

> I don't have an 060.  My question is, should I also put Forbid_ before t=
he
> end, so my program will work OK with a user's 060?

 Simple answer: you don't need to.

 Long answer/no relevance:

 No, Blitz generates 68000 machine code, which works on all 68k's. Putting=
 
Forbid_ before an End statement would be changing the operation of the pro=
gram, 
with repesct to the OS, not the processor.

 Every Blitz program I've run works on my 060 (unless there is actually 
something wrong with the code [i.e. crashes on all other machines as well]=
). 
Blitz also works fine with this config:
	Blizzard 1260@50
	Blitz 2.1
	STed 2.24
	LES DBugger 1.21 (the one on Aminet)

 No amount of system hack commodities, changing caches, or using 
[Cyber/Oxy]Patcher changes the crashability of Blitz.

 Maybe the BSS versions of the programs cause problems? Or maybe Blitz doe=
sn't 
like Apollo boards? Or maybe that CIA bug in your Amiga....


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
