@NODE "Mail_11" "Re: 2 mice"
From: Sami =?iso-8859-1?Q?N=E4=E4t=E4nen?= <sami.naatanen@dlc.fi>
Date: Thu, 10 Dec 1998 21:18:41 +0300
Subject: Re: 2 mice
Encoding: quoted-printable

 Paul taped from his/her keyboard.

On 09-Dec-98, you wrote:

>   Hi,
>   =

>  >> There are lots of ways to impliment it but the basic method
>  >> is based aroun the values peeked at at:-
>   =

>  >> Peek.b($dff00d) ; X speed...
>  >> Peek.b($dff00c) ; Y speed...
>   =

>  >> I'm sure you can take it from there...
>   =

>  > Nice, what's the addies for the first port ?
>   =

>   Oi, NO!!! ;)
>   =

>   I guess thre is a valid reason fo knowing how to read the first port =
using
>   the
>   same method but I'm sorry I don't know what the addresses are. I'd gu=
ess
>   they're quite close to these nd perhaps a little experiment with a lo=
ad of
>   'peeks' and some mouse movement would give these addresses away.
>   =

>   Cheers,
>   =


Well these are word addresses so you should read these as words!

joy0dat $dff00a port 0 (the one you normally stick your mouse)
joy1dat $dff00c port 1 (the joyjoy port ;)

So the reading will be done like this:

; a.w is temporary variable to store the input

x.b=3D0 ; current X counter value
y.b=3D0 ; current Y counter value

xx.b=3D0 ; previous X counter value
yy.b=3D0 ; previous Y counter value

mx.w=3D0 ; pointer X cordinate
my.w=3D0 ; pointer Y cordinate


a.w=3Dpoke.w($dff00a)
x.b=3D(a lsr 8)&$ff
y.b=3Da&$ff

if x.b<>xx.b
  temp.b=3Dxx.b
  x.b-xx.b
  xx.b=3Dtemp.b
  mx.w+x.b
endif

if y.b<>yy.b
  temp.b=3Dyy.b
  y.b-yy.b
  yy.b=3Dtemp.b
  my.w+y.b
endif


   _____________________________________________________________
  |                                                             |
  | Sami N=E4=E4t=E4nen   A1260 50MB 3.5GB 2X 56k BJC-4100 HP Deskjet |
  | EMail: sami.naatanen@dlc.fi                                 |
  |                                                             |
