Date: Wed, 09 Dec 1998 15:46:39 +0100
From: stifter@mira.cz
Subject: 24bit graphics

Hello,

a friend of mine asked me, how is it possible to have
24bit graphics on graphics cards ?

Opening a screen and attaching  a 24bit deep chunky bitmap or
what ?

Has anybody done it yet ?

Thanks



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_13" "Re: 24bit graphics"
 ([62.136.1.95] helo=sneech ident=paul)
	by mail3.svr.pol.co.uk with smtp (Exim 2.05iplimit-2 #5)
	id 0zo8Qh-00053F-00
	for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 10 Dec 1998 15:55:03 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Date: Thu, 10 Dec 1998 15:06:02 +0000
Subject: Re: 24bit graphics

Hi,

> a friend of mine asked me, how is it possible to have
> 24bit graphics on graphics cards ?
> Opening a screen and attaching  a 24bit deep chunky bitmap or
> what ?

You're kind of right. Basicly you'd allocate a 24bit bitmap and use
cybergraphx.library functions to get information about it. gfx-card
screens can use many different formats for colour allocation
such as

PIXFMT_LUT8   <--- i think this is normal 256 colour chunky
PIXFMT_RGB15
PIXFMT_BGR15
PIXFMT_RGB15PC
PIXFMT_BGR15PC
PIXFMT_RGB16
PIXFMT_BGR16
PIXFMT_RGB16PC
PIXFMT_BGR16PC
PIXFMT_RGB24
PIXFMT_BGR24
PIXFMT_ARGB32
PIXFMT_BGRA32
PIXFMT_RGBA32

Using cybergraphics you can decide which kind of bitmap/ screen to open
and/or detect what kind is open. You'd probably want to open the RGB24
mode or maybe even stick to RGB16 for a little extra speed.

Once you've opened your bitmap you can use LockBitmapTags_() to
lock it. This will return an address where it is now safe to 'poke' into.

Please remember that when i talk about bitmaps I'm taking about AmigaOS
bitmaps not Blitz ones! Please downlod the cybergraphics developer
kit from aminet (CGraphX-DevKit.lha dev/misc 44K) for more info. If
you don't understand it then it's best to forget about 24bit support. I've
only had very little experience with specific cybergraphx coding because
if you stick to 8bit games or standard graphics.library coding you'll never
have a need to use cybergraphics!

> Has anybody done it yet ?

I plan to look into 16bit or 24bit graphics for my game but thats a
long way off at the moment. It's probably best to experiment with
standard 8bit cybergraphics code using te real cybergraphics
functions rather than the graphics.library. Once you've mastered
that it'll be no problem moving up into more complex pixel modes.

Cheers,

-- 
< Paul Burkey - http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk >

"Pump their brains full of magic monkey juice."
-- On the Hour



