@NODE "Mail_21" "Re: 3D Experts Group ?"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Sat, 05 Dec 1998 14:32:26 +1200
Subject: Re: 3D Experts Group ?
Encoding: quoted-printable

On 05-Dec-98, Mikkel L=F8kke wrote:
> =

>> It's probably best to wait for Warp3D and build an engine based
>> on that. There's no way you're going to support 3D cards with
>> Blitz alone and 68k is just not good enough for the kind of thing
>> you'd want to see in a modern 3D engine.

>Why does everyone seem to think the Haage-Partners can do everything so
>muuch better ?

  Well, what other option is there to their work? Certainly not P5 with
their non-existant documentation on the PowerUp OS (seeing as it's a new
and unknown OS, the docs are terrible!!).

 Besides, it's very restraining to build an Engine on a
>"standard" API, because even if you had something really powerfull,
>(Like
>say a SillyGfx) you would still be limited to the functions offered by
>Warp3D ?

  It really comes down to hardware concepts. Should you use customised
GFX hardware like 3DFX chips as a co-processor? Or should all 3D work be
done by the main cpu(s), and have multiple processors like the BeBox
instead? It comes down to, is the 3D chip more efficient at 3D
processing, or is it better to be able to put in more CPU's for more
gruntier effects which can be updated in software instead of having to
buy a new 3D effects card for better graphics (you'd still have to buy
new/better CPU's for the second option)?
 Buggered if I know!!!   :-)

> Besides from what I gatherred, Warp3D is not to be a stand
>alone
>API, but more like an extension of Storm C. I may, ofcourse, be
>mistaken.

  It would be standard Amiga libraries wouldn't it? Accessable by any
language I would assume.
 =

