@NODE "Mail_22" "Re: 3D Experts Group ?"
 ([62.136.38.108] helo=sneech ident=paul)
	by mail4.svr.pol.co.uk with smtp (Exim 2.05iplimit-2 #5)
	id 0zm8PK-000166-00
	for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Sat, 5 Dec 1998 03:29:22 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Date: Sat, 05 Dec 1998 02:56:20 +0000
Subject: Re: 3D Experts Group ?

Hi,

>> It's probably best to wait for Warp3D and build an engine based
>> on that. There's no way you're going to support 3D cards with
>> Blitz alone and 68k is just not good enough for the kind of thing
>> you'd want to see in a modern 3D engine.

> Why does everyone seem to think the Haage-Partners can do everything so
> muuch better ? Besides, it's very restraining to build an Engine on a
> "standard" API, because even if you had something really powerfull, (Like
> say a SillyGfx) you would still be limited to the functions offered by
> Warp3D ? Besides from what I gatherred, Warp3D is not to be a stand alone
> API, but more like an extension of Storm C. I may, ofcourse, be mistaken.

I think you're mistaken on this last point but I'm not 100% sure. I only
mentioned Warp3D because I think it's a very foolish idea to spend
a lot of time developing a 3D engine without using some kind of
3D standard like Warp3D or OpenGL etc. unless you were to do it in
a portable language and you planned to develop for a market that
could make it worthwhile. You'd have to ensure compatability with all
Amiga 3D cards as well as good solid PPC support because no other
Amiga system can handle a modern 3D game. You don't need to
*limit* yourself to the functions of Warp3D however you should wait
and see what it has to offer and plan things around it. If Warp3D
provides an instant solution to 50% of your game engine with very
little effort then whats the problem? 

Cheers,

-- 
< Paul Burkey - http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk >



@ENDNODE
