> Define worthwhile ?

worthwhile would be when many users get to use the end product. This
could be as little as a few thousand but unless the system supported PPC
and 3D cards I doubt any 3D system would get many users at all unless
we're talking about 3D technolody that is less advaned than Quake.

>> Amiga 3D cards as well as good solid PPC support because no other
>> Amiga system can handle a modern 3D game. You don't need to

> Agreed. However, we could hope that AMiGA would go the same way as
> Nintendo, using SGI, in this case we would have a processor that does
> OpenGL for fun :o) And if AMiGA's have OpenGL allready (like AMiGA Inc.
> claim) it would be very easy to convert the current OpenGL games for the
> PC. Another thing to keep in mind is that 3Dfx have their own "OpenGL"
> languuge thingy which they use for their Voodoo line of 3D accellerators.
> So, which standard is really a standard ? Well, I'd say Direct 3D is the
> closest to a standard API, but not really an option for the 10% of the
> market that don't have wintel machines.

Well I would guess that all these 'standards' have some similarities
but i have to back down when it comes this kind of thing. All I really
want to see is a way of minimizing the work that needs to be done
by utilizing any standards that come along. If we have OpenGL,
Warp3D, GLide (?) or Direct 3D then it would be smart to use one
of these rather than seeing everyone make their own API. I guess
thats why we don't need another CyberGFX/P96 or another AHI
on the current 'classic amiga'.

>> *limit* yourself to the functions of Warp3D however you should wait
>> and see what it has to offer and plan things around it. If Warp3D
>> provides an instant solution to 50% of your game engine with very
>> little effort then whats the problem? 

> The last 50%. The thing is that Haage-Partners claim it's like OpenGL (but
> not compatible), and everyone thinks it's Direct3D...

okay so really I wanted to say 80% (or more) but I also wanted to make
it clear that I'm only suggesting to 'wait and see what we can use' before
anyone starts making something from scratch.

Cheers,

