@NODE "Mail_25" "3D Gone Mad??"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Mon, 7 Dec 1998 00:06:43 +0000
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: 3D Gone Mad??
Date: Sun, 6 Dec 1998 21:34:42 -0000
	boundary="----=_NextPart_000_000C_01BE2160.3C517160"

This is a multi-part message in MIME format.

------=_NextPart_000_000C_01BE2160.3C517160
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hello all,

 Just wanted to add a few points to this *ahem* discussion....

 When the type of 3d programming were talked about started on the pc, =
the top pc was a 486. Most video cards only had 512k of ram (some even =
less). All of the 3d stuff was written to run under dos (not win3.1 as =
that`s useless). They wrote most of it in C and coded the small =
repetitive stuff in asm for more speed (sound familar??). Generally they =
used double buffering (cos the speed of drawing a frame was pretty slow) =
which was usually done in normal ram, then copied to the display using =
longword copying (sound familar??). These displays were in a planar type =
format (sound familar??). And in general...the games ran quite slow, =
even doom (unless you shrunk the screen).

 These days..the general rule is to use win95 with a 3d library, use c++ =
and very little asm (if any at all!) (as most of the 3d work isn`t done =
directly by you anyway, so there isn`t really anything to optimize under =
asm). Ignore the frame rate as if it`s slow, you simply tell everyone =
how it`s doing all this cool stuff.

 The trouble is, that were still at the early stage..as were supporting =
the majority of amiga users left, not the handful of ppl with ppc amigas =
(though, if blitz had a ppc library, that could help the problem, as you =
could just release the same thing in ppc, only I`d imagine that the ppc =
version wouldn`t be much better...just a better frame rate, as it`d =
still have the same gfx etc.). And I doubt that the amiga market could =
change over night. Even if we had lots of new amigas in the shops, =
people have to buy them, software companies have to support them.

 As I suggested before..worry less about making a kick ass 3D =
engine..and more about making a good game. I only class 3D games as =
games where you can freely move about in a 3D environment, not isometric =
games, or 2D games with 3D elements. But if you do spend the time, and =
make a great looking, very fast 3D engine on the amiga (possible on ppc, =
fairly useless for an 060 [not a big enough user base..who is gonna buy =
a 060 for games, when you can get PPC and 040 for less??], unlikely on a =
030) you could make a good game and while your at it earn some money!

Happy 3d`ing...

Dave

P.s. I might just transfer some old 3d code from my pc just to see how =
fast it really is ;)



------=_NextPart_000_000C_01BE2160.3C517160
