@NODE "Mail_45" "Re: 3D Quake Clone"
Date: Sat, 05 Dec 1998 13:47:41 +1300
From: Julian Kinraid <jkinraid@clear.net.nz>
X-Accept-Language: en-GB,en
Subject: Re: 3D Quake Clone
Encoding: quoted-printable

Fr=E9d=E9ric Laboureur wrote:
> =

>     Hi Paul,
> =

> > Probably just C. In my recent experiments the C language is very
> > fast and can do most things as fast as Asm unless you spend a
> > lot of time hand optimizing. On a platform like the PC where super
> > fast 250Mhz cpu's are dirt cheap this kind of hand optimizing is
> > a waste of time which should be spent on more productive things
> > like gameplay :) This is what I hope the event of super 3D gfx-cards
> > will bring. On the Amiga you can spend weeks hand optimizing your
> > code and people will still complain it's too slow. Once again Quake
> > is a good example.
> =

>     Probably C code is fast (yes it is) BUT please don't say that it's =
as
> fast than hand written ASM one. Even the most optimized C routine is at=

> least 3 time faster when rewritten in ASM. To be convinced, just try to=

> write a fast c2p in C langage. Try and send me the result ;=B0).

Are you sure about that?  A c2p is rather specialised, so no wonder
someone can write a fast one is asm.  But what about C routines like
strcpy()?  With function inlining, loop unrolling, register allocation,
instruction scheduling, profiling, bla bla bla, I would say that writing
an asm version would be a complete waste of time.  The best way (IMO) is
to write a program in a language like C (or Blitz, E, whatever), find
the parts that take the most time, and write them in asm.

Compilers are becoming more advanced, and even the 'register' keyword in
C has been pointless for a while (with a decent compiler), because the
compiler is much better at assigning registers to the most used
variables.  Also, with RISC CPUs, AFAIK, a C compiler can produce very
good code compared to assembly because it can handle the pipelines and
instruction scheduling much better than a human.  So while the PPC asm
coder is optimising his/her routines to the max, the C coder has changed
his/her routine to a much better one...

I seem to remember that Quake on the PC was optimised so that while FPU
instructions were being calculated, integer instructions were also being
done 'for 'free'.

--
Julian Kinraid


@ENDNODE
