>>     Probably C code is fast (yes it is) BUT please don't say that it's=

as
>> fast than hand written ASM one. Even the most optimized C routine is a=
t
>> least 3 time faster when rewritten in ASM. To be convinced, just try t=
o
>> write a fast c2p in C langage. Try and send me the result ;=B0).

> Are you sure about that?  A c2p is rather specialised, so no wonder
> someone can write a fast one is asm.  But what about C routines like
> strcpy()?  With function inlining, loop unrolling, register allocation,=

> instruction scheduling, profiling, bla bla bla, I would say that writin=
g
> an asm version would be a complete waste of time.  The best way (IMO) i=
s
> to write a program in a language like C (or Blitz, E, whatever), find
> the parts that take the most time, and write them in asm.

> Compilers are becoming more advanced, and even the 'register' keyword i=
n
> C has been pointless for a while (with a decent compiler), because the
> compiler is much better at assigning registers to the most used
> variables.  Also, with RISC CPUs, AFAIK, a C compiler can produce very
> good code compared to assembly because it can handle the pipelines and
> instruction scheduling much better than a human.  So while the PPC asm
> coder is optimising his/her routines to the max, the C coder has change=
d
> his/her routine to a much better one...

Amusing theory. Please remember that C compilers are written buy humans,
and
that they are not sentient. C compilers WILL produce slower code than the=

authour (of the C compiiler) could do in plain asm. It is a fact of life.=

Another thing, intelligent coders will certainly make sure the most used
part of their code is small enough to fit inside the cache, C programmers=

have no control over this, (or am I mistaken ?) and have to hope that thi=
er
C compiler outputs code small enough to fit in caches etc. Now with most
modern PC's with a 1MB cache (Wow, a PC now has more cache than convetion=
al
memory. Evolution :o) ) , this is of no real concern, on AMiGA's however
this is indeed a considerable concern.


Regards
