Hi,

>> Compilers are becoming more advanced, and even the 'register' keyword in
>> C has been pointless for a while (with a decent compiler), because the
>> compiler is much better at assigning registers to the most used
>> variables.  

> Amusing theory. Please remember that C compilers are written buy humans,
> and that they are not sentient. C compilers WILL produce slower code than
> the authour (of the C compiiler) could do in plain asm.

Using these rules you'd say that Lightwave can only make pictures
that are up to the standard of the lightwave programmer. You see
the programmer knows all about how light works, how shading works,
how ambient light affects the scene and many other factors that
go into rendering a picture. The computer follows these set rules and
can do a much better job than any human could. The same thing
can happen with a C compiler if the human provides enough
information about the target system.

> Another thing, intelligent coders will certainly make sure the most used
> part of their code is small enough to fit inside the cache, C programmers
> have no control over this, (or am I mistaken ?) and have to hope that
thier
> C compiler outputs code small enough to fit in caches etc.

compiler options? Any experienced C programmer will know how
to produce C code that produced small efficient code as compared
to your standard 'easy to follow' ansi stuff. Once again, a modern C
compiler can do wonders if you feed it efficient source.

Cheers,

-- 
