@NODE "Mail_59" "Re: 3D Quake Clone"
Date: Sun, 06 Dec 1998 15:37:33 +1300
From: Julian Kinraid <jkinraid@clear.net.nz>
X-Accept-Language: en-GB,en
Subject: Re: 3D Quake Clone
Encoding: quoted-printable

Fr=E9d=E9ric Laboureur wrote:
> =

>     Hi Julian,
> =

> > Are you sure about that?  A c2p is rather specialised, so no wonder
> > someone can write a fast one is asm.  But what about C routines like
> > strcpy()?  With function inlining, loop unrolling, register allocatio=
n,
> > instruction scheduling, profiling, bla bla bla, I would say that writ=
ing
> > an asm version would be a complete waste of time.
> =

>     What of terms ! :-). Really, do you think than you can do a faster
> strcpy() routine in C than the one done in ASM ?
> =

> ; a0 =3D startaddr
> ; a1 =3D destaddr
> _StrCopyLoop:
>     MOVE.b  (a0)+, d0
>     MOVE.b  d0, (a1)+
>     TST.b   d0            ; Check if it's the end of string...
>     BNE    _StrCopyLoop

You said 'Even the most optimized C routine is at least 3 time faster
when rewritten in ASM'.  Lets assume you are writing a program in C. =

You write a asmstrcpy routine, like yours above.  When you do a strcpy,
the compiler puts the start address in a0, the end address in a1.  It
then jsr's to the asmstrcpy routine.

Now, with a C routine (as long as the compiler has the source for
strcpy()), it can first put the function inline.  It can then perform
loop unrolling, and it can use whatever registers it wants (instead of
*having* to use a0 and a1), so it can make better use of the available
registers.  And in the end, there is no point with the asm version. =

Just writing a routine in asm won't magically make it go 3 times faster.

[snip]

> > Compilers are becoming more advanced, and even the 'register' keyword=
 in
> > C has been pointless for a while (with a decent compiler), because th=
e
> > compiler is much better at assigning registers to the most used
> > variables.  Also, with RISC CPUs, AFAIK, a C compiler can produce ver=
y
> > good code compared to assembly because it can handle the pipelines an=
d
> > instruction scheduling much better than a human.  So while the PPC as=
m
> > coder is optimising his/her routines to the max, the C coder has chan=
ged
> > his/her routine to a much better one...
> =

>     You seems to forget than descent ASM compiler do the pipelining, ca=
ching
> and all little tricks than humans can't do itself. So if you have a ver=
y
> fast routine at the basis, with optimizing it would be lightining fast.=


The same thing can be said for a decent C compiler.  Sure, the bottom
line is that writing in asm generates faster code, but in terms of a
whole project, the more time you can spend on development rather than
worrying about cycles here and there, the better.  I'm not saying that
writing in assembly useless, just that it has a niche.  I doubt anyone
disagrees with that, so this thread should be ending soon :)

I've written a program (in C) that tokenises ASCII blitz source a *hell*
of a lot faster than Blitz.  If I wanted, I could make it even faster, =

without resorting to assembly.  Why is it faster?  Because it uses a
better routine than Blitz does.

--
Julian Kinraid



@ENDNODE
