@NODE "Mail_61" "Re: 3D Quake Clone"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Sun, 06 Dec 1998 17:34:23 +1200
Subject: Re: 3D Quake Clone

On 05-Dec-98, Paul Burkey wrote:
 
>I would also like to claim that using 3D cards is the way to go. Who
>wants to see game programmers having to hand optimize 3d routines,
>texture mapping, shading, filtering etc.. I think it's better to work
on
>the game itself and leave the 3D stuff to the experts (3Dfx etc.) who
>can make super fast and cheap hardware.
 
  Do you think it's more efficient than having multi-processors and a 3D
lib written in assem? Are 3D gfx chips cheaper comparably to an CPU that
could do the same work? Just interested :-)

>I never said you shouldn't optimize but I do think optimized portable C
>is much more clever than optimized Asm. I don't mind working in Asm
>for small jobs lik c2p, p2c, chunky blitting, special gfx effects etc..
>but
>thats where I'd draw the line. This is why we all like to use Blitz..
we
>all
>know it's not as fast as C or ASm but it's much faster an asier to
>develop
>with which means projects can get huge AND easy to keep control of.

  I think a good use af assem, is in the inner loop of a 3D engine- ie:
the bit that executes for every pixel. on a 640*512 screen thats 
327,680 times per frame! So any assem optimisations would be multiplied
by 327,680. Even a small benefit would become large- even if you didn't
write the whole inner loop in assem, you could do bits of it! This 
*would* make the assem work worthwhile, outside the loop would be a
waste of time of course!
 
-- 
