@NODE "Mail_81" "500% Speedup compared to GetReg"
Date: Wed, 02 Dec 1998 16:14:44 +0100
From: Manfred Linzner <manfred.linzner@munich.netsurf.de>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: 500% Speedup compared to GetReg
Encoding: 7bit


I always wondered why the GetReg in BB2 commando is soo slow.
On my 68030/50 i can only do ~4.000 Getreg commands on
a longword. With some change you can do 20.000!!
An easy solution for this is the following


Normal code:

Deftype.l a
a=1000
Getreg a0,a

Fast code:

Deftype.l a
a=1000
Move.l d0,a0


BB2 simply puts you currently used var into D0.
So move it wherever you want. You just have
to access the needed var before (i.e. a=a works also).

I hope someone finds this usefull because it seems
that todays coders doesnt take a look on optimization =)

Manfred


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_82" "Re: 500% Speedup compared to GetReg"
From: =?iso-8859-1?Q?Fr=E9d=E9ric?= Laboureur <alphasnd@sdv.fr>
Date: Wed, 02 Dec 1998 19:05:33 +0100
Organization: Fantaisie Software
Subject: Re: 500% Speedup compared to GetReg
Encoding: quoted-printable

    Hi Manfred, =


> I always wondered why the GetReg in BB2 commando is soo slow.
> On my 68030/50 i can only do ~4.000 Getreg commands on
> a longword. With some change you can do 20.000!!
> An easy solution for this is the following

    It takes so lot of time because all the command perform a such
operation:

    MOVEM.l ; save used register
    JSR  Command ; exec the command
    MOVEM.l ; restore registers

    So you can imagine the time lost at every call :)   =


> Normal code:
> =

> Deftype.l a
> a=3D1000
> Getreg a0,a
> =

> Fast code:
> =

> Deftype.l a
> a=3D1000
> Move.l d0,a0

    Great to know !
 =

> BB2 simply puts you currently used var into D0.
> So move it wherever you want. You just have
> to access the needed var before (i.e. a=3Da works also).
> =

> I hope someone finds this usefull because it seems
> that todays coders doesnt take a look on optimization =3D)

    I find it useful, thanks ! And I like a lot optimizations :)
    I always though than powerful CPU shouldn't say don't optimize your
code. =


        Bye,
                        Fred.

