@NODE "Mail_119" "Re: Aminet Censored!? - (Maybe) Off Topic!"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sun, 13 Dec 1998 18:06:51 -0500
Subject: Re: Aminet Censored!? - (Maybe) Off Topic!
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hi Mikkel

On 13-Dec-98, Mikkel L=F8kke wrote:
> On 12-Dec-98, Andrew wrote:
> =

>> Blitz isn't default to any chip set.  I could open screens for any
>> chip set thay every come out.  Most blitz programes are going more
>> so called O/S freindly ways. I hear lot less about Blitz mode then did=

>> say 8 mounths ago.   =


> Well, the Blitz mode has nothing to do with any specific chipsets, nor =
is
> it particularily OS unfriendly. It just that people use this interestin=
g
> way of addressing the AMiGA's hardware without REALLY knowing what
they're
> doing, (Which is not surprising at all, since AMiGA NEVER printed an AG=
A
> specific HRM). So most people decide to use Intuition screens, not beca=
se
> they're nessecarilly better, but because there is much less hassle.

Actually, Blitz-mode is OS unfriendly in the sense that it disables the O=
S -
no multi-tasking while your program is running, no TCP available, etc.

It doesn't "harm" the OS - it is still there when your program is finishe=
d,
but nothing else can happen until then.

Also using Blitz-mode makes your program instantly incompatable with GFX
cards.
And probably any future hardware.

Later...

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_120" "Re: Aminet Censored!? - (Maybe) Off Topic!"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Mon, 14 Dec 1998 04:27:11 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 14 Dec 98 04:26:34 +0000
Subject: Re: Aminet Censored!? - (Maybe) Off Topic!
Encoding: 7bit

Curt,

> Actually, Blitz-mode is OS unfriendly in the sense that it disables the OS -
> no multi-tasking while your program is running, no TCP available, etc.

Also disables the interrupts which I find has the most effect on
speed.
 
> It doesn't "harm" the OS - it is still there when your program is finished,
> but nothing else can happen until then.
> 
> Also using Blitz-mode makes your program instantly incompatable with GFX
> cards.
> And probably any future hardware.

That's not entirely true. If you were looking to have graphics-card
support in your game you would be working in chunky and using c2p.
Wether that c2p outputs to an intuition screen or a blitzmode display
is neither here nor there. Although, I think what you mean is that the
traditional blitz mode in which you also use special hardware features
(copperlists etc), sprites etc makes it more difficult to produce a
gfx-compatible mode.

-- 
Paul.

