@NODE "Mail_136" "Re: Blitz CPU routine for arcade game"
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <FlameDuck@usa.net>
Date: Sat, 26 Dec 1998 02:38:29 +0200
Organization: A97
Subject: Re: Blitz CPU routine for arcade game
Encoding: quoted-printable
X-Info: mailto:sf@xxl.ots.dk in case of problems!

On 25-Dec-98, Philippe Bovier wrote:

> - I search after the best CPU Blitz library for using in an arcade
> game. The mildred archive can be used for that or This routine is
> principally based for c2p for doom clone ??? No problem now for
> searching in internet site now :-)

Ah, well you see contrary to popular belief c2p is usfull for doing much
more than just your average DOOM clone. Look at NAPALM for a good example=
and all of the latest AMiGA demoes. (The Party comming up soon, there is
bound to be some massive releases up there) :o)

Actually there are many reasons to prefer "Chunky" (or byte per pixel)
displays over planar ones. =


1. Graphics cards work in this way.
2. Special effects, like firework and pixel explosion are easy to do.
3. Speed. Setting a single point only takes one byte to be moved, instead=
 of
8. (allthough this is offset on c2p time on planar displays)
4. Well basically all sorts of special effects, bitmap warping, texture
maping, shadows, fire trails aso. are really (or at least comparativly)
easier to do in chunky.

=46rom what I've seen of mildred (quite alot really), it truely rocks, an=
d I
would warmly recomend it to anyone. (Unless you're an ace assembly coder
and insist on using your own code). =



Regards
-- =

