@NODE "Mail_167" "Re: Blitz Source Check V0.4b"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 08 Dec 1998 06:37:37 -0500
Subject: Re: Blitz Source Check V0.4b

Hi Paul,

On 07-Dec-98, Paul Burkey wrote:
> Hi,
> 
> Here's a new version of Blitz Source Check which will now parse
> an ascii text version of your Blitz code and check for various errors
> or warnings. These now include Obsolete SHARED variables,
> Unused Functions/Statements and Statements/Functions with incorrect
> or missing End Statement/End Function. I've done a little bit of
> optimizing and it manages to parse half a meg of code in 40 seconds
> on my system which isn't too bad considering it was searching for
> quite a lot of stuff ie, the existance of any of 260 function calls in
> 20,000 lines of code. The program is designed to be used once in
> a while or at the 'clean up stage' or a frustrating bug finding session.
> It's not meant to be used every day and you'll rarely be running half
> meg sources through it so i think it's "Fast Enough(tm)" ;)
> 
> It should 'in theory' work with 99% accuracy now too!

Thanks, Paul.  A very useful utility.

One question - it reported a shared variable as obsolete that was used
elsewhere in the program.  This was a pointer (*myvariable).

Did the program make a mistake, or isn't it necessary to share  * type
variables?

Later...
-- 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_168" "Re: Blitz Source Check V0.4b"
 ([62.136.53.99] helo=sneech ident=paul)
	by mail7.svr.pol.co.uk with smtp (Exim 2.05iplimit-2 #5)
	id 0znYqL-0004Dw-00
	for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Wed, 9 Dec 1998 01:55:09 +0000
From: blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie
Date: Wed, 09 Dec 1998 01:31:58 +0000
Subject: Re: Blitz Source Check V0.4b

Hi,

> One question - it reported a shared variable as obsolete that was used
> elsewhere in the program.  This was a pointer (*myvariable).
> Did the program make a mistake, or isn't it necessary to share  * type
> variables?

Was the shared variable used in th function that contained the shared
command? If so I'll have to fix it... If the '*myvariable' was used in
the statement then it would require the shared command. Maybe
it's just a confusion in the wording of the warning message. If you're
sure that there is an error you could send some short source code to
me to help fix the bug.

Cheers,

-- 
< Paul Burkey - http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk >



@ENDNODE
