@NODE "Mail_192" "Colorfont remapping"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    11 Dec 98 14:02:30 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Fri, 11 Dec 1998 14:02:17 -0000
Subject: Colorfont remapping


--Message-Boundary-8559
encoding: Quoted-printable
Content-description: Mail message body

 For anyone who cares, here's some source to remap colorfonts. There are s=
ome 
problems with it, but it works and shouldn't crash (unless you try). This =
isn't 
meant to be for casual use, so there isn't any error checking, feel free t=
o add 
some.

 Problems:
1) The font cannot be remapped to anything other than at new depth boundar=
ies, 
i.e. you can only remap a colorfont which uses colors 0-7 to use colors 8-=
15. 
I'm going to change this, so that you can change the colours to any positi=
on in 
the palette.

2) Because it changes the font data in memory, any other programs which op=
en 
this font will get the altered one. I'm also going to change this so that =
it 
uses a copy of the font.

3) Assumes that there will be enough colours available on screen + a few o=
her 
assumptions.

 This principle can also be used for remapping bitmaps. All it does ATM, i=
s 
create an extra bitplane which contains all 1's thus causing all the colou=
rs 
used to be increased by 2^(new bitplane number).


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694
  http://members.xoom.com/David_McMinn

