@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_195" "Re: Colour Fonts"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    10 Dec 98 09:13:54 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Thu, 10 Dec 1998 09:13:49 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: Colour Fonts

On 9 Dec 98, at 20:53, Curt Esser wrote:

> > Does anyone know how to use two colour fonts at the same time each wit=
h
> > their own palette. I've got two 8 colour fonts which I want to use on
> > the window at the same time. Any ideas?
> 
> You could convert one to a 16 colour font, using only the last 8 colours=
.
> Then set your palette colours # 0 - 15 to correspond to the fonts colour=
s.
> (assuming your screen has 16 or more colours?)

 Yes, that would work. See later.

> > Also, does the palette information for the colour fonts have to start =
at
> 0
> > in the palette?
> 
> I think it does, since colourfonts are really a series of "brushes" or
> "shapes".

 No, it doesn't have to start at 0. There's two fields which specify the l=
ower 
and upper bounds of the colours used by the font. The palette information =
in 
the colorfont "specifies the colors used by this font" (according to the 
RKRMs), so they would only contain palette information for colours 3 to 8 =
(if 
they were your bounds). I think the code in my example is therefore wrong,=
 as 
it just assumes they will start from 0.

 I'll check my code again to see if it does need fixing, and if possible c=
ould 
someone send me a font where the colours used do *not* start at 0, I don't=
 have 
any font editors.

 Internally fonts are stored as one large bitplane, with each character 
described as an offset (left edge of the image) and a width. Colorfonts si=
mply 
have multiple bitplanes.


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694
  http://members.xoom.com/David_McMinn


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_196" "Continuing problem with Freq!"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Mon, 21 Dec 1998 19:46:16 +0000
From: "Peter Nightingale" <rajpete@andos.freeserve.co.uk>
Subject: Continuing problem with Freq!
Date: Mon, 21 Dec 1998 19:45:58 -0000
	boundary="----=_NextPart_000_000D_01BE2D1A.881AA600"

This is a multi-part message in MIME format.

------=_NextPart_000_000D_01BE2D1A.881AA600
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hi..
In the following bit of code, (taken from a larger program) the first =
`Freq 8,blah` works perfectly, and the second (at the bottom) stops the =
sample playing on channel 2. This is driving me insane! Does anybody =
have any idea why?
BTW thanks to Curt Esser for the source of his similar (working) =
program.

LoadSound 0,"dh0:whitenoise"
LoadSound 1,"dh0:sinewave"
LoadSound 2,"dh0:sinewave"

LoopSound 0,1,0
waite{25}                                                                =
  ; this just vwait 25
LoopSound 0,2,0
LoopSound 1,4,0
LoopSound 2,8,0
Freq 3,250
Freq 4,#k/(107*bse)
Freq 8,#k/(107*(bse+sweepf))
GTSetString 1,0,"Playing..."
Window 2,50,15,200,50,$2|$4,"Playing...",1,0
GTText 2,0,72,3,110,14,"Status:",1,"Fading in..."
GTButton 2,1,47,20,100,14,"Abort",0
AttachGTList 2,2
For I.l=3D1 To 64
  waite{2}
  Volume 15,I,I,I,I
  If Event=3D$40
    Gosub quitsound
    exit.l=3D-1
    I.l=3D64
  EndIf
Next I
If exit.l=3D-1 Then Return
S.f=3Dsweepf.f
steps.f=3D(fre.f-sweepf.f)/(sweept.f*60)
Freq 8,#k/(107*(S.f-0.1))

Thanks
Peter Nightingale

------=_NextPart_000_000D_01BE2D1A.881AA600
