@NODE "Mail_214" "Re: CreateNewProc()"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    21 Dec 98 11:00:54 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Mon, 21 Dec 1998 11:00:46 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: CreateNewProc()

Hello,

> How do I use the CreateNewProc() call in blitz? If I do something
> like this:
> 
> Dim tags.TagItem(3)
> 
> tags(0)=3D#NP_Entry,?newproc
> tags(1)=3D#NP_Name,"My New Task"
> tags(2)=3D#TAG_DONE,0

Change those three to:

procname$=3D"My new task"; This never changes

tags(0)\ti_Tag=3D#NP_Entry,?newproc
tags(1)\ti_Tag=3D#NP_Name,&procname$
tags(2)\ti_Tag=3D#TAG_END,0

> *proc.l=3DCreateNewProc_(tags(0))

 And this to *proc.l=3DCreateNewProc_(&tags(0))

> newproc:
> Nprint "hello world"
> RTS

 Are you sure that the new process will ingherit all your variables, inclu=
ding 
stuff Blitz allocates (i.e. opening of dos.library, etc.). For your sanity=
, I 
hope this is true.


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694
  http://members.xoom.com/David_McMinn


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_215" "Re: CreateNewProc()"
          Paris Mon, 21 Dec 1998 14:56:47 +0100 (MET)
Date: Mon, 21 Dec 1998 15:00:27 +0100
From: "v.demongodin@wanadoo.fr" <v.demongodin@wanadoo.fr>
X-Accept-Language: fr,en
Subject: Re: CreateNewProc()
Encoding: 7bit



Andreas Falkenhahn wrote:

> Hi !!
>
> How do I use the CreateNewProc() call in blitz? If I do something
> like this:
>
> Dim tags.TagItem(3)
>
> tags(0)=#NP_Entry,?newproc
> tags(1)=#NP_Name,"My New Task"
> tags(2)=#TAG_DONE,0
>
> *proc.l=CreateNewProc_(tags(0))
>
> MouseWait
>
> End
>
> newproc:
> Nprint "hello world"
> RTS
>
> It doesn`t work.
>
> Any idea?
>
> --
> A merry christmas and a happy new year wishes
>
>            Andreas
>

BB2 use a4-a6 registers to find variables, functions and statement in memory,
you need to save and
restore this registers in a absolute memory location:

Add a

.SaveRegister:
Dcl.l 0,0,0

at the end of code

Before createNewproc_(.....):
    Movem.l  a4-a6,SaveRegister

After newproc:
    Movem.l SaveRegister,a4-a6

But on more complex code, things be more complex, because you normaly can't
share library pointer with 2 or more tasks...


Vincent.
Old A1200 - 68030/fpu 50Mhz - 32Mo Ram - DD 500 Mo - Very Old VGA display...



