Subject: Re: Enigma.


Hello Stephen Fellner

 
> But you shouldn't need to do something like that. I am also using
> borderblanked screens, and it's no problem in any screenmodes. Although I
> can't check PAL or NTSC or EURO36, as my monitor is VGA only and it'll
> only sync down to about 23-34 khz.
> 
> I have attached two files for you:
> 
> 1. Monded - With this one you can definately get rid of that line in
> multisync modes! I think the fourth slider can adjust the left start
> position for scanning. If you increase it by one, your gray line should
> disappear. (Don't blow your monitor, although I've been playing around
> with moned on all kinds of monitors without killing any, but oyu never
> know... just be careful :-)
> 
> 2. Monitor30Patch - You should install these monitor drivers before you
> try moned. They are newer versions than most people have as wall as a
> newer an much better version of IPrefs and the Overscan perferences
> programs. (Make sure the installer doesn't overwrite your setpatch as I
> have a later setpatch than the one in the archive. Once installed and if
> your grey line is still there, try adjusting the screen size in the
> overscan preferences. If still no luck, you can always fix the multiscan
> modes with moned, but you can't change PAL and NTSC with moned as those
> are hardcoded into the machine, so maybe oyu have an older motherboard
> revision or something...
> 
> What kind of monitor do you have ? Do you get the gray lines even when
> using the composite video output (built-in on an A1200 or with a TV
> Modulator) ?
> 

Wow, thanks for these, I`ll try them out tonight.  In case you`re 
interested, I`ve got a SVGA monitor with scan boubler. No, it`s not 
the scan dounbler thats causing fault, cause it was present with 
my NTSC/Pal monitor (although not all the time).  I was thinking 
maybe setpatch was the problem...

Thanks
Steven



