@NODE "Mail_252" "Re: Finding Screens"
From: Mika Jussila <krf@saunalahti.fi>
Date: Sun, 01 Jan 1978 00:51:40 +0200
Organization: the krafted syndikate!
Subject: Re: Finding Screens

Reply to a message from Jake Frederick (15-Dec-98):
>How can I find the name of all open screens? I then want to be able to pop
any
>one of them to the front. I'm making a screen manager program that handles
>screens in the same way Windoze 98 handles open programs with a bar at the
>bottom that allows you to go to whichever program you click on. 

IntuitionBase has the pointer to the first open screen.. Just start there and
go trough every screen (with *Screen=*Screen\NextScreen) until *NextScreen
fails (is NULL)...

-- 
*** - Mika "Mehiz" Jussila / G-Men Projects & krafted innovations!



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_253" "Re: Finding Screens"
From: Mika Jussila <krf@saunalahti.fi>
Date: Sun, 01 Jan 1978 01:03:46 +0200
Organization: the krafted syndikate!
Subject: Re: Finding Screens

Reply to a message from Mika Jussila (01-Jan-78):
>Reply to a message from Jake Frederick (15-Dec-98):
>>How can I find the name of all open screens? I then want to be able to pop
>any
>>one of them to the front. I'm making a screen manager program that handles
>>screens in the same way Windoze 98 handles open programs with a bar at the
>>bottom that allows you to go to whichever program you click on. 

>IntuitionBase has the pointer to the first open screen.. Just start there and
>go trough every screen (with *Screen=*Screen\NextScreen) until *NextScreen
>fails (is NULL)...

Oh yes, and the name of the screen can be found at *Screen\Title and the
default title at *Screen\DefaultTitle :)
These are pointers to a null terminated strings so you can read 'em to a
string variable eg. using Name.s=Peek$(*Screen\Title)...

If you're not familiar with these system structures feel free to ask for some
further guidance :)
 
*** - Mika "Mehiz" Jussila / G-Men Projects & krafted innovations!



@ENDNODE
