@NODE "Mail_267" "Re: Freq command"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 18 Dec 1998 14:10:46 -0500
Subject: Re: Freq command
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hi,

On 18-Dec-98, Mikkel L=F8kke wrote:
> Hello Peter.
> =

> On 18-Dec-98, Peter Nightingale wrote:
>> Hi...
>> I`m having problems with Freq.. when I use it on channelmask 8 (only
>> channel 3) it stops the sample on channel 2( channelmask 4, it think)!=

Is
>> there an alternative command I could use?
> =

> I'm sure there is a mistake in the above maths, however I havn't slept =
in
> 32 hours, so I'm too damned tired to figure it out.

No, the channelmasks he shows are correct.  But there must be something
else
to blame.  We used the Freq command extensively in our BeatBox2 program, =
affect only certain channels, and never had any problems.

Just to be sure, I added a second sound to my "motor-pitch-change" test
program, and set the channelmasks as you did.  So one sound plays only on=

channel 2 continously, with no pitch change, and the other only on channe=
l
3, with pitch controlled by the joystick position.  =


Everything works perfectly, no interference between the two sounds at all=
=2E =

I can send you the example if you want.

An alternate command would be SetPeriod, which changes the actual pitch
value in the sound object itself.  To use SetPeriod, you must turn the
de-bugger off, and I don't think it can be used while the sound is alread=
y
playing.

Another way would be to poke the frequency value directly into the
appropriate place in the sound object, if you're feeling brave   ;)

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
