@NODE "Mail_275" "GFX card screenmodes"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 28 Dec 1998 05:49:49 -0500
Subject: GFX card screenmodes

Hi everybody,

I am converting a game to be GFX card compatable.

So, there must be a screenmode requester to be able to use your GFX card's
screenmodes, right?

Unfortunately, I don't have a GFX card, so I need your help:

1} The game uses a standard lo-res screen, so I will be using David McMinn's
hook function code to eliminate the other modes.  This works for my
standard system, but does this also work for GFX card modes?  If not, is
there some way to eliminate everything but lo-res 8bit GFX card modes from
the requester?

2} For standard systems, there is no point in having the "Depth" selector
since the game is obviously meant to run at a particular depth.  Do I need
to show a depth selector for GFX card screens? (the required screen will be
less than 256 colours on standard systems)

3} Ideally, it would be best if I could simply do away with the mode
requester altogether, and "autodetect" if a GFX card is in use, and somehow
tell my program to just open a low-res GFX card screen rather than a
standard planar screen.  Is this possible?

Thanks for you help, and Happy New Year to you all...

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_276" "GFX Card screens?"
From: Luca Carminati <toffi@spm.it>
Date: Mon, 28 Dec 1998 14:37:02 -0500
Subject: GFX Card screens?
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hi friends,

I coded a tool for saving open screens as IFF-ILBM pictures. It works per=
fectly for AGA screens (up to 8 bitplanes) but a guy told me that screens=
 on gfx cards are saved as messed pictures (even with just 4 colors). I d=
on't have a gfx card so I cannot do any test. Is there anyone who can tel=
l me if the bitmap data on gfx cards are stored in a different way (I rea=
d the data from the screen's bitmap structure)?



-- =

Best regards,

Luca.

