@NODE "Mail_278" "Re: Gfx Card users please help"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Wed, 30 Dec 1998 01:06:20 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 30 Dec 98 01:05:45 +0000
Subject: Re: Gfx Card users please help
Encoding: 7bit

Hi Curt,

Your screenmode requester test showed the following list of
screenmodes on my system. I have an Ateo Pixel64 and/or AGA.
I'll also list the default size that these modes give when clicked on
(for `text size' overscan)...

NTSC:Low Res    AGA              320x200
PAL:Low Res     AGA              320x256
Paul64:320x240  gfx-card 8bit    320x240
Paul64:320x240  gfx-card 16-bit  320x240
Paul64:320x240  gfx-card 32bit   320x240
Pixel64:320x240 gfx-card 8bit    320x240
Pixel64:320x240 gfx-card 16bit   320x240
Pixel64:320x240 gfx-card 24bit   320x240
Pixel64:320x240 gfx-card 32bit   320x240

So as you can see you are successfully restraining the screen
dimensions, but you are not managing to filter out the hi-colour and
true-colour modes. To do this, you need to use something like
FindDisplayInfo_ and GetDisplayInfo_  (whatever it's called). You will
then find a `max depth' parameter in one of the structures. If the max
depth is higher than 8 you can bet your life it's almost definately
going to be a non-colourmapped mode such as hi-colour or true-colour.
It usually returns 16 for hi-colour and 32 for true-colour.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



@ENDNODE
