> say was : You print some text at a certian position on a Window... =

> after you`ve printed how do you tell where the cursor is?  I suppose =

> I could use TextLength_ but this slows my routine down quite =

> dramatically.

   Ok, I've added these functions for you ! I've attached the new Window.=
obj
file to this mail. New functions are :

    + NWCursX, NWCursY
    + NWInnerHeight, NWInnerWidth

    Remember that NWCurs functions can be altered by some GFX functions
(Especially NLine).  =

 =

> Also, what about the WBlit commands? Oh wait forget that - I =

> could use BltBitMapRastPort_

    In the NCS V1.50, you have FULL Blit support trough the BitMap/Pictur=
e
libraries:

    Use the following code:

        NInitBitmap 0
        NinitPicture 0

        NLoadPicture 0, "Test.iff"

        NBitMap 0, NPictureWidth, NPictureHeight, NPictureDepth

        ; Open your window,

        NDrawingOutput NWindowRastport

        NCopyBitMap 0, .....

   And you will have clean bitmap to window... In fact, NCopyBitmap =3D W=
Blit.

> Ah but there is something - how do you set the attributes of a =

> gadget after it has been created. eg Say I have a gtmx gadget and =

> the user presses key "a". How do I set it say that the gtmx goes to =

> the first option?  I thought about SetGadgetAttributes_ but I can`t =

> find a pointer to the gadget

    When you create a NGaget, you can get it's own pointer:

    *StrinGadget1 =3D NStringGadget(0....)
 =

    Easy ?

> Thanks for listening

    My Pleasure,

                        Fred.

<sb>

        /\/\/\/\/\                    Fr=E9d=E9ric Laboureur (Fred)
     __/          \_    =

    /^ ^  u^ ^n  ^ ^\               E-Mail Address: alphasnd@sdv.fr =

   (o o_ /(o o)\ _o o)  =

  _/_ /// |   | \\\ _\_              Only Amiga makes it possible
 (o_o)//  (o o)  \\(o_o)            Quality software for the Amiga
  `---'   `---'   `---'             =

 F-Base  TheBoss  F-Bench         AlphaSOUND - FANTAISIE Software (1998)

