@NODE "Mail_322" "GTString problems"
From: "Tony Rolfe" <edgewater@shoalhaven.net.au>
Organization: Edgewater Motel, Burrill Lake, NSW 2539 Australia
Date: 2 Dec 98 16:22:58 +1000
Subject: GTString problems
Encoding: 7bit

I'm using GTString for all data input and validating numbers, dates,
etc.   No probs so far.  

However, coming from an IBM Mainframe background, I've always used
Return/Enter keys to go from field to field.  These don't
automagically activate the next field, which is cool because I often
don't want to go to the next field so I activate the gadget myself.

Problem1.  I've just discovered that TAB key works just like Return,
except that it activates the next gadget and when I try to then
activate a different one the second gadget won't activate.  Does
anyone know how to deactivate a gadget?  I guess simulating a mouse
click on a blank part of the window would do it.

Problem 2.  How do I tell whether the user hit return, enter, TAB or
Shift-Tab?  

Problem 3.  How can I simulate clickind a GTButton with the keyboard? 
I know that you can use _ characters to underline a hot key, but how
do you make them work?

Thanks in advance


-- 
Tony Rolfe
Amiga 2000, 68030/25, 1+4Mb
www.shoalhaven.net.au/edgewater


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_323" "Re: GTString problems"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    2 Dec 98 10:09:24 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Wed, 2 Dec 1998 10:09:18 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: GTString problems

On 2 Dec 98, at 16:22, Tony Rolfe wrote:

> Problem1.  I've just discovered that TAB key works just like Return,
> except that it activates the next gadget and when I try to then
> activate a different one the second gadget won't activate.  Does
> anyone know how to deactivate a gadget?  I guess simulating a mouse
> click on a blank part of the window would do it.

Why not create your gadgets in the order that you will move between 
then using TAB? <Check RKRM> Yep, thats what it says to do.
 
> Problem 2.  How do I tell whether the user hit return, enter, TAB or
> Shift-Tab?

You will get a #IDCMP_GADGETUP message, with the gadget being 
returned by GadgetHit and the key that caused it being the EventCode. 
So EventCode will be 9 (ASCII for TAB), and you should check the 
Qualifier result to see if the Shift keys have been used (therefore a 
Shift-TAB).

> Problem 3.  How can I simulate clickind a GTButton with the keyboard? I
> know that you can use _ characters to underline a hot key, but how do yo=
u
> make them work?

 You need a section in your event handling code for keypresses. If 
the key pressed is one of your shortcut keys, then the program should 
do whatever it does when that GTButton is clicked. Its also possible 
to highlight the button, even though the RKRMs say you can't. I'll 
send you the code if you want it.


