@NODE "Mail_328" "Re: GTString problems"
          Paris Sun, 6 Dec 1998 21:09:49 +0100 (MET)
From: Gigandet Jean-Marc <HURRICAN@wanadoo.fr>
Date: Sat, 05 Dec 1998 11:07:52 +0100
Subject: Re: GTString problems
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hello Tony,

Your big and really only problem is to stop Tab cycling !
And *THIS* can be done.
Ok it's not really an easy way, but it's the sytem one.
First define your gadgets, then before opening the Window get the structu=
res of the gadget and modify the GFLG_TABCYCLE flag to false ! Your gadge=
ts won't participate any more in cycling activation.
Want some code ? Here it is ...

#FindScreen 0#
##
#GTString 0,50,140,10,120,18,"With Tab Gt1",1,10,"Value 1"#
#GTString 0,51,140,30,120,18,"With Tab Gt2",1,10,"Value 2"#
#GTString 0,52,140,50,120,18,"No   Tab Gt3",1,10,"Value 3"#
#*StrGad52.Gadget =3D GTGadPtr(0,52)#
#*StrGad52\Flags =3D  *StrGad52\Flags - $200        ; Remove GFLG_TABCYCL=
E flag !#
##
#Window 0,20,0,320,140,$100F,"HELLO",1,2#
##
#AttachGTList 0,0#
##
#ActivateString 0,50#
##
##
#Repeat#
#  ev.l=3DWaitEvent#
#Until ev=3D$200#
##
#End#
##

Regards
-- =

HURRICAN@wanadoo.fr
A1200 030/28 + 68881 + 8 Mo + Quantum 635 Mo + Wd 60 Mo + M1438S + Deskje=
t 690C + UsR 33600.
HURRICANE, TURRICAN, well, that's a good mix. Both should visit Redmond .=
=2E.



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_329" "GTStrings + Highlighting GTButtons"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    4 Dec 98 11:17:38 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Fri, 4 Dec 1998 11:17:27 -0000
Subject: GTStrings + Highlighting GTButtons


--Message-Boundary-24300
encoding: Quoted-printable
Content-description: Mail message body

 These two archives contain source for highlighting GTButtons and activati=
ng
the desired GTString.

 The GTButton source can be done a number of other ways. This version uses
GTToggle, but you could also set the flags for the gadget (possible future
incompatibilities) or you could draw a box over the GTButton using an
exclusive OR drawing mode (to highlight and return to normal). You can may=
be
even use the proper commands for setting the attributes (similar to the fl=
ags).

 The GTString source is a kind of hack, as there is no way to deactivate a
string gadget, which you need to do before activating another.  The way I'=
ve
done it is to disable then enable the active string gadget, to deactivate =
it.
This disable/enable may be displayed more than you want, depending on the
speed of your processor / system load etc. Note that the normal Blitz2
Qualifier command doesn't return the qualifier for gadget up events, so yo=
u
either have to use the NCS or OS routines. Examples for both are provided.
Also note that there probably isn't an easy way to highlight gadgets on
keypresses when a string gadget is active. Without getting into custom edi=
t
hooks and other assorted profanities.

 Sorry about the lack of comments in the sources, I'll do an explanation i=
f 
anyone wants it.


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694
  http://members.xoom.com/David_McMinn

