Oh no.First it was PFS (Which was shareware), then it was AFS (Which was =
a
comercial package released by 4th Level Development) and now it's back to=

PFS, because too many people have trusted their HD's to AFS and lost. :o)=

And isn't it strange that for a package that has been released for so lon=
g
(8 years to my counting) there is still not a single disc recovery progra=
m
that fully supports it (Dave Haynie's disksalv ALMOST does it.) The
arguement is that PFS (AFS, whatever FS) is so good that it just isn't
necesary. Strange then that the package carries a HUGE disclaimer, writte=
n
all in capitols, in bold, and in red writing that they won't take any
responsibility for dataloss. I bought the original AFS package, and I hav=
e
lost one HD (No, not just the files, an entire HD, completely fucked, in =
a
hardware sense of way.) and another (different, obviously) HD that
allthough it works today with FFS, still has wierd quirks sometimes. I te=
ll
you, do not trust PFS more than you would Windoze98. (Which is probably a=

bit harsh on the PFS/AFS guys, since it's not as crap as windows, but it
gets an A for effort) :o)


Regards
