Hi S
Am 23-Dez-98 schrieb S Beardwood:

> Hello,
> 
> Can any one help with converting the c source below to blitz.
> 
> UBYTE *Mod;
> ULONG ModSize;
> 
> *struct TagItem ModAttrTags[]=
>     {
>      {DBMATTR_InstNum,0},
>      {DBMATTR_ChanNum,0},
>      {DBMATTR_PattNum,0},
>      {DBMATTR_ModName,0},
>      {DBMATTR_InstNames,0},
>      {TAG_DONE,0}
>     };
> 
> 
> ULONG InstrNum;
> ULONG ChanNum;
> ULONG PattNum;
> STRPTR ModName;
> STRPTR *InstNames;
> 
> ModAttrTags[0].ti_Data = (ULONG)&InstrNum;
> ModAttrTags[1].ti_Data = (ULONG)&ChanNum;
> ModAttrTags[2].ti_Data = (ULONG)&PattNum;
> ModAttrTags[3].ti_Data = (ULONG)&ModName;
> ModAttrTags[4].ti_Data = (ULONG)&InstNames;
That is easy. Just dim an array and set the tags,
e.g. ModAttrTags(0)\ti_Data = #DBMATTR_InstrNum,0
But don`t forget to convert the include files to
blitz.
> 
> printf("%d\n",InstrNum);
> printf("%d\n",ChanNum);
> printf("%d\n",PattNum);
> printf("%s\n",ModName);
You do not need to care about printing different
variable types in blitz. You can just do
Nprint InstrNum for example.
> 
> for(i=0;i<InstrNum;i++)
> {
>  printf("%s\n",InstNames[i]);
>  }
> 
You can use something like this here:

i=0
While i<InstrNum
      Nprint InstNames(i)
      i=i+1
Wend

That should do it.     
> 
> All The Best, 
Regards
-- 
