@NODE "Mail_367" "Re: How"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Wed, 02 Dec 1998 14:36:41 +1200
Subject: Re: How

On 02-Dec-98, Paul wrote:
>Hi.

>How do you do animation that is dependent on a fixed movement speed
>that appears to travel the same distance in a given space of time
>regardless of the framerate?

  Well, that's a bit tricky in 2D- you'd really have to know what frame
rates it would run at. Say if your shape runs at 1 pixel per frame at 50
fps (50 pixels per second), then at 25 fps it would have to move at 2
pixels per frame (to still move at the set 50 pixels per second). If say
your first animation ran at 50fps, then at 25fps, you'd have to skip
every second frame in the animation. So you really have to tweak each
animation for known frame rates- in 3D it's simple as the whole display
is drawn each frame. 
  You might have to redo the animation for say 60fps, or do the old
dropping a frame every 6 frames to convert NTSC->PAL (60fps->50fps).
This works ok at high framerates like 50fps, but you'd have to be
careful at slower (under 25 fps) rates. 
  Maybe converting from high rates you could just do a mathmatical
routine to automatically convert as above, but converting from slow
rates to slow rates you'd have to tweak by hand.

-- 
