Subject: Re: How does Setint work?

On 10-Dec-98, stocksjames wrote:
>Hi
>I was wondering how 'setint' works. I usually include it to play music:

>Setint 5
>PlayMed
>End Setint

>Is 'PlayMed' executed on EVERY vertical refresh, or just those called by
>the program?

Afaik it says that at a certain interval it needs to execute(handle) the
code inbetween the setint x and the end setint forever, until you do a
clearint x. Setint 5 is vertical scanrate, like vwait, so 50 or 60
times/sec. 

Its difficult for me to get interrupts working, as blitz doesnt like it in
if endif and statements etc. So i have to do a goto or gosub(out of the
main loop) to the
interrupt(perferably at the end of the code, to a place where the
programflow normally wouldnt go to if u didnt specifically state it) when 
I want to play the med and then return. The interrupt continues to work until 
u do a clrint, which follows normally a stopmodule. Oh yes, as stated in the 
manual, if u try to do any intuition, os, string and other related things in 
an interrupt its instant crash. I tried a gtsetinteger and it crashed no 
matter what :-) 

In a way i find interrupt programming rather cool 8-)

Regards

