@NODE "Mail_399" "IsCyberModeID (Can P96 users test it?)"
 ([62.136.34.142] helo=sneech ident=paul)
	by mail8.svr.pol.co.uk with smtp (Exim 2.05iplimit-2 #5)
	id 0zlbNJ-0002Se-00
	for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 3 Dec 1998 16:13:05 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Date: Thu, 03 Dec 1998 16:05:48 +0000
Subject: IsCyberModeID (Can P96 users test it?)

Warning: This is a message in MIME format. Your mail reader does not
support MIME. Some parts of this message will be readable as plain text.
To see the rest, you will need to upgrade your mail reader.


--BOUNDARY.1746391976.2

Hi,

I recently provided some source to open a screen mode requester
and examine the screen mode ID for Native AGA modes or foreign
Cybergfx/P96 modes. This is to allow my game to use different code
depending on the type of screen opened. The previous modeid test
seemed to work but with one major problem. All my 8bit gfx card
modes were recognized as Native! I think this has something to do
with the fact that an 8bit mode in cybergfx should normaly be treated
as the same albeit planar or chunky, it should be the OS's job to
deal with the differences. While this is fine for most AmigaOS work
it's not fine for a game, especially when some Blitz's graphic functions
don't work on gfx card screens (ie, ShowBitmap etc..)

So, I decided to access cybergraphics.library itself in order to use
the IsCyberModeID_() function which seems to detect the difference
between PAL and CGFX without fail. I presume that P96 would also
give the same results since P96 supports the CyberGFX API which
I guess means that any application that tries to open the cybergraphics
library would be fooled into thinking it was successful. I can only
presume further into the fact that IsCyberModeID_() would return
a TRUE for P96 modes too. If not I'll have to hunt down the P96
developer files and add support for IsPicassoModeID_() or whatever
the equivelent is.

Anyway, I've attached an archive that contains a test program
that will open a requester and attempt to detect foreign modes
using a mixture of IsCyberModeID and the DisplayInfo structure.
Coul someone with P96 test this out for me? I'm hoping it will
work with P96 as well as CyberGFX.

I've included the simple source code and also the ready converted
'cybergraphics.library1' blitz lib that is required for this special
function. The source is a bit crude but it should do it's job! :)

Cheers

-- 
< Paul Burkey - http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk >

"Hardest game in the world"
-- Fast Show

--BOUNDARY.1746391976.2
