@NODE "Mail_431" "Mildred 1.2"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Sat, 12 Dec 1998 02:33:08 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 12 Dec 98 02:32:29 +0000
Subject: Mildred 1.2
Encoding: 7bit

Hi folks.

Just keeping you updated. Mildred v1.2 is now on-line. I have added
two commands which you might find of use, I remember there was some
talk of this a while back.

MReMap
MReMapShape

The paremeters can either be

Table.l

or

Table.l,BitmapNum.w

or

Colour0.b,Colour1.b,BitmapNum.w

Sorry but I can't figure a way to make use of the currently used
bitmap object so you have to specify it.

MReMap is of course for performing a remap on a bitmap and MReMapShape
is to do the same on a shape. You can specify a colour which will be
altered using the three-parameter version, in which any pixels of
Colour0 (value) will be remapped to Colour1 (value). Alternatively you
can specify a table. This is simply a 256-byte table of numbers
telling the routine what to change each of the colours to. So for
example, contents of 5, 240, 122, 17 would cause pixels of colour 0 to
be changed to colour 5, pixels of colour 1 to be changed to colour
240, etc.

A combination of MPlanar16ToBitmap, MReMap, and Mc2p is quite an
interesting one and probably quite fast. I'd imagine it'd be
much faster than doing the same thing in planar. Using a table is many
times faster than remapping each colour in a seperate call and it is
worth using a table to remap any more than 1 colour. On my 040/25 with
a 320x256 AGA screen open, it takes about 2/50ths to remap every
colour in the image, or about 7/50th's to remap 640x512. This of
course doesn't include planar-to-chunky and chunky-to-planar time.

-- 
Paul.

