@NODE "Mail_465" "Re: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)"
From: Marcel Weber <mw@caverock.net.nz>
Date: Thu, 03 Dec 1998 13:14:50 +1200
Subject: Re: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)

Hello Mikkel

On 29-Nov-98, you wrote:

> Hello Marcel.
> 
> On 26-Nov-98, Marcel Weber wrote:
>
> <removed to save you some download time>
>
> You should allways start your programs with the
> NewPaletteMode On command. This way Use Palette works the way it's
SUPPOSED
> to. :o)

Thanks I'll add that in and cross my fingers.

>> 3) The game only updates the parts of the display that change.
>> Unfortunately when there is a large explosion much more has to be 
>> updated and the game slows down. Is there a way to limit the framerate
>> accurately without chewing up CPU time? Currently I use Ticks and a 
>> while loop. However Ticks are only accurate to the nearest 50th or 60th
>> of a second and I need more than that. Any ideas?
> 
> First of, WHY would you need more than 1/50th of a second ? And from what
I
> can read you are chewing up tons of CPU time. The "professinal" way of
> doing it is to do different parts of your code each frame. This way your
> game WON'T go at 50fps (Not a huge problem, since the eye cannot detect
> more than 12-13) but the spare time can be used for all kinds of effects.
I
> can recomend the WaitTOF_ command, which is an OS friendly counterpart to
> VWAit, which doesn't cause CPU overhead.

I need more than 1/50th of a second to accurately record the time taken to
draw a single frame. That the eye cannot detect more than 12-13 fps doesn't
seem very relevant since a game running at 50fps looks FAR better than one
at 12 fps. I think Donovan Reeve sent a detailed message to this list about
fps and graphics earlier on suggesting that frame rates be kept  above 35.
In order to do that I need to time the frames and find out if the speed
drops by too much. I guess its not possible in Blitz without opening the
timer.device.

Performing different parts of your code each frame is a brilliant idea and I
already do that to some extent but thanks for the suggestion, I think I
will try and do even more of this. Of course this only applies when
calculation is the problem. My main problem is drawing graphics and I can't
really draw part of the graphics one frame and part the next since this
would probably make the game appear to slow down anyway.

Recent versions were using WaitTOF_ and it is cetainly much better than
vwait although I can only work out how to limit the framerate at 50, 25 or
12.5 ... fps by using a number of WaitTOF_'s.

-- 

Marcel Weber <mw@caverock.co.nz>
(Xar on #Amiga Undernet/AmigaNet)



