@NODE "Mail_471" "Peeking and poking around in memory"
From: "Oliver Marks" <oly@enterprise.net>
Organization: Private
Date: 27 Dec 98 14:32:29 +0000
Subject: Peeking and poking around in memory 
Encoding: 7bit

Hi,

I have been trying to implement linked list code into my program
somebody was kind enough to send me the code but i was having trouble
figuring out how it works so started playing around with the commands
that where being used.

I am having trouble with the code below basically it displays the
string and then crashes can anyone tell me why?

The only commands in the code that i have ever used before are
wbstartup nprint len() and mousewait so you can undersatnd why i am
having trouble with this code it is all relativley new to me.

WBStartup
NEWTYPE .LL
    *text.b
    front.l
    rear.l
End NEWTYPE

DEFTYPE.LL *mem
head.l=0
counter=0
name$ = "Hello"
*mem = AllocMem_ (Len(name$)+7,#MEMF_ANY)
Poke$ *mem\text,name$
Poke.l *mem\front,*mem
Poke.l *mem\rear,*mem
head = *mem\front

NPrint Peek.l(*mem\front)
NPrint Peek.l(*mem\rear)
NPrint Peek$(*mem\text)
MouseWait









@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_472" "Re: Peeking and poking around in memory"
Date: Mon, 28 Dec 1998 16:01:47 +1300
From: Julian Kinraid <jkinraid@clear.net.nz>
X-Accept-Language: en-GB,en
Subject: Re: Peeking and poking around in memory
Encoding: 7bit

Hi Oliver,

> I have been trying to implement linked list code into my program
> somebody was kind enough to send me the code but i was having trouble
> figuring out how it works so started playing around with the commands
> that where being used.
> 
> I am having trouble with the code below basically it displays the
> string and then crashes can anyone tell me why?
> 
> The only commands in the code that i have ever used before are
> wbstartup nprint len() and mousewait so you can undersatnd why i am
> having trouble with this code it is all relativley new to me.
> 
> WBStartup
> NEWTYPE .LL
>     *text.b
>     front.l
>     rear.l
> End NEWTYPE
> 
> DEFTYPE.LL *mem

*mem is used as a pointer, and it is up to the user to create the space
needed.

> head.l=0
> counter=0
> name$ = "Hello"
> *mem = AllocMem_ (Len(name$)+7,#MEMF_ANY)

This is wrong because you first need to allocate memory for *mem.

*mem = AllocMem_ (Sizeof.LL, #MEMF_ANY)

This will allocate 12 bytes of space that is used to store the *text.b
pointer and the front & rear values.  Remember a pointer is always 4
bytes, whether it is a pointer to a byte (*pointer.b) or to a long
(*pointer.l)

Then you need to allocate memory for the string.

*mem\text = AllocMem_ (Len(name$) + 1, #MEMF_ANY)

> Poke$ *mem\text,name$

> Poke.l *mem\front,*mem
> Poke.l *mem\rear,*mem

You don't need to use Poke for these, Blitz will extract the values from
the LL type for you -

*mem\front = *mem
*mem\rear  = *mem

> head = *mem\front
> 
> NPrint Peek.l(*mem\front)
> NPrint Peek.l(*mem\rear)
> NPrint Peek$(*mem\text)
> MouseWait

--
Julian Kinraid


@ENDNODE
