@NODE "Mail_492" "Re: Pointers and Lib Probs"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    22 Dec 98 10:10:18 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Tue, 22 Dec 1998 10:10:09 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: Pointers and Lib Probs

On 21 Dec 98, at 22:35, Bippy M wrote:

> Could some kind person please explain a few things to me!
> 
> 1). Please, Please explain (In simple terms) Pointers and how to use the=
m

Pointers are a way of being able to specify where in memory a variable is.=
 For  
example *bite.b =3D 100 would allow you to access memory at address 100. Y=
ou 
don't ever do this though, you normally assign the pointers to the result =
of 
commands, or to the address of variables. The address of a variable is got=
 
using &variablename. The address of a label in a program is got using 
?labelname.

 Pointers are most commonly used with newtypes, as Blitz doesn't really ha=
ndle 
.b, .w, .l or .q properly as pointers - you need to use them in conjuction=
 with 
Peek and Poke, or a custom newtype.

Example - print items from array using pointers:

#ARRSIZE =3D 10
Dim array.w(#ARRSIZE)
For i.w=3D0 To #ARRSIZE-1
    array(i) =3D Rnd(100)		; Fill array with some bnumbers
Next

*ptr.w =3D &array(0)			; Get address of first item in array
For i.w=3D0 To #ARRSIZE-1
	NPrint Peek.w(*ptr)		; Peek at the word stored at the address pointed to
							; by *ptr
	*ptr =3D *ptr + Sizeof.w	; Increase address by size of word (mnoves onto
							; next item in array)
Next
Clickmouse
End

> 2). Also, explain TAGS as I haven't a clue,
>   2a). How does the system recognise them etc..

 Tags are an extension to the OS, they allow you to set flags and paramete=
rs 
for commands without having to use 100000 registers. In the TagItem newtyp=
e, 
the ti_Tag field specifies the tag that is being set, and the ti_Data fiel=
d is 
what you are setting it to (or some other command specific thing). A tag w=
ith 
ti_Tag field set to #TAG_END represents the end of the array of tags. You 
should use an array of TagItems rather than a newtype with 20 or so variab=
les 
of .l type, as its easier to understand.

Example: setting a tag array (you need to include amigalibs.res)

Dim tags.TagItem(5)		; 5 is the number of tags we are going to set + 1 for
						; the end tag

tags(0)\ti_Tag =3D #WA_Dragbar, True
tags(1)\ti_Tag =3D #WA_CloseGadget, True
tags(2)\ti_Tag =3D #WA_Width, 300
tags(3)\ti_Tag =3D #WA_Height, 200
tags(4)\ti_Tag =3D #TAG_END

 To pass a taglist to a function, use &tags(0).

 Tags are always documented in the autodocs, so get a copy of them. These =
4 
tags above set four things for a window - says that we want a draggable wi=
ndow, 
a closegadget, a width of 300 and a height of 200.

 The system recognises them by, well, it just does. Depending on the funct=
ion 
called, it will recognise the different tags and set any flags or variable=
s as 
appropriate.

> 3). How do you open a window using Tag/Pointers (Some SIMPLE source woul=
d
> be
>              appreciated )

WBToScreen 0
WBenchToFront_
Dim tags.TagItem(5)
tags(0)\ti_Tag=3D#WA_Left,0
tags(1)\ti_Tag=3D#WA_Top,0
tags(2)\ti_Tag=3D#WA_Width,300
tags(3)\ti_Tag=3D#WA_Height,200
tags(4)\ti_Tag=3D#TAG_END
WindowTags 0,$100f,"My window",&tags(0)
While WaitEvent<>#IDCMP_CLOSEGADGET
Wend
End

--------------- YOUR OTHER MESSAGE ---------------

> I've got a small Problem with a FD I've converted (Using James Boyles
> Proggy)

