@NODE "Mail_494" "Pointers, Arrays and things"
From: "Tony Rolfe" <edgewater@shoalhaven.net.au>
Organization: Edgewater Motel, Burrill Lake, NSW 2539 Australia
Date: 30 Dec 98 14:45:47 +1000
Subject: Pointers, Arrays and things
Encoding: 7bit

Hi,

I wonder if anyone can help with a small problem.

I have a file, the Fields statements look like:

Fields #xrf_file,xrf_next.l
Fields #xrf_file,xrf_pointer.l

What I want is to dynamically allocate memory for the file, load it in
via the ReadMem statement and access it as though it was an array.

Now, I know that I have to define a newtype with the fields backwards
(coz that's how the Put statement write them).

Newtype .xrf
xrf_pointer.l
xrf_next.l
End Newtype

I then have to allocate memory for the array

If NOT OpenFile(#xrf_file,"Motel:Motel.Xrf")
   << error message etc.>>
EndIf
*Mem.l = AllocMem_(LOF(#xrf_file,#MEMF_ANY))  
(I don't know this syntax properly)

Then I need to dimension an array and associate it with the memory
(which I haven't the foggiest idea how to do).  Is is something like:

DIM *xrf_array(LOF(#xrf_file)/sizeof .xrf)
 Which should define the array, but how do I get it to use the memory
I've allocated.

Finally, I read the data into the array

FileSeek #xref_file,0   ; to ensure I'm at the start
ReadMem #xref_file,&xrf_Array,LOF(#xrf_file)
(Do I need the & here or should I use *Mem or just Mem?)

Any help would be greatly appreciated.

Thanks

-- 
Tony Rolfe
Amiga 2000, 68030/25, 1+4Mb
www.shoalhaven.net.au/edgewater


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_495" "Re: Pointers, Arrays and things"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Wed, 30 Dec 1998 13:57:30 +0000
From: "David McMinn" <dmcminn@house-of-mojo.freeserve.co.uk>
Organization: International House of Mojo
Date: Wed, 30 Dec 1998 13:49:25 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: Pointers, Arrays and things

On 30 Dec 98, at 14:45, Tony broke out long enough to write:

> I then have to allocate memory for the array
> 
> If NOT OpenFile(#xrf_file,"Motel:Motel.Xrf")
>    << error message etc.>>
> EndIf
> *Mem.l =3D AllocMem_(LOF(#xrf_file,#MEMF_ANY))  
> (I don't know this syntax properly)

OK, it should be:
*Mem.l =3D AllocMem_(LOF(#xrf_file),#MEMF_PUBLIC))
 You should also check that you have actually been allocated the memory by=
 
checking if *Mem=3D0 and handling this error case.  

> Then I need to dimension an array and associate it with the memory
> (which I haven't the foggiest idea how to do).  Is is something like:
> 
> DIM *xrf_array(LOF(#xrf_file)/sizeof .xrf)
>  Which should define the array, but how do I get it to use the memory I'=
ve
> allocated.

 Nope, you can't do anything fancy at all like that. What you need to do i=
s 
have a pointer which is used to access the array. If you want to access th=
e 
element number 5 in the array, you do: 
*ptr =3D *Mem + Sizeof.xrf * 5 ; You could always use a variable instead o=
f 5

> Finally, I read the data into the array
> 
> FileSeek #xref_file,0   ; to ensure I'm at the start
> ReadMem #xref_file,&xrf_Array,LOF(#xrf_file)
> (Do I need the & here or should I use *Mem or just Mem?)

ReadMem #xref_file,*Mem,LOF(#xref_file) should do it.


