From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <FlameDuck@usa.net>
Date: Thu, 24 Dec 1998 00:07:31 +0200
Organization: A97
Subject: Re: Q
Encoding: quoted-printable
X-Info: mailto:sf@xxl.ots.dk in case of problems!

On 22-Dec-98, Paul wrote:

> Does anyone know how to get the o/s 3.1 function `WriteChunkyPixels_'
> to become a token in Blitz?

I think every one else covered this pretty good so far. My  cents worth i=
s
that if you where to convert the OS3.1 functions you would probably have
Blitz screw up trying to figure out which of the 2 identical calls it
should use. =


> Does anyone know where in memory/structs to obtain a number
> representing what CPU the user has (as returned by the Processor
> instrurction)?

Hehe, this is a real tricky one. I heard this on an ASM coder mailing lis=
t
quite some time ago, and appearently it depends on which processor board
the user has. It goes something like this:

If you have a standard AMiGA you will get the correct number from exec.

If you have a WarpEngine you will get a 0. (Erm ups. Cool, my kick arse 0=
40
accelerater is an 68000.) There are patches to this. All are hacks.

If you have a CyberStorm I think it will set bit #7. (See below.)

If you have CyberStorm Mk. 2 or 3 you will get a 040 result + an extra bi=
t,
somewhere. (Bit #7, if I recall correctly) This was done so even badly
written code would at least think it was using a 040 :o)

PPC cards ? Well, both WarpOS and PowerUP libraries have commands which
return A. CISC Processor, B. RISC Processor, and C. Clock Freq. (Allthoug=
h
the Clock is the frequency of the PowerUP board (as opposed to the CPU)an=
d
either 33, 28 or 25.)

Now all of this might be wrong, as I'm writing this down of the top of my=

head as good as I remember it. However, I can get my hands on a System
Analysis program one of my friends wrote. It's in ASM though, and probabl=
y
not very well documented. I hope you don't mind. :o)


> Does anyone know how to find out what version of o/s is available
> (with regards the WriteChunkyPixels thing)?

Erm, I think that system analysis program does this aswell. :o)


Regards
