@NODE "Mail_509" "Re: Q"
From: Rick Hodger <rick.thehub@bigfoot.com>
Date: Thu, 24 Dec 1998 12:23:31 +0000
Organization: Corrupted Software
Subject: Re: Q

I watched as David Mcminn hammered "Re: Q" out on their keyboard...

>> Does anyone know where in memory/structs to obtain a number
>> representing what CPU the user has (as returned by the Processor
>> instrurction)?

> Tsk, tsk, don't randomly jab about in memory. Its possible to read
the 
> AttnFlags in the execbase, (*e.ExecBase = Peek.l(4):*e\AttnFlags)
but thats a 
> big future compatible no-no (I don't even know if that has flags for
PPCs, it 
> doesn't normally for 060). Check out the includes for the processor
flags. Also 
> the Devs CD tells you how to read what processor you have properly,
but I can't 
> remember if it was an OS function, or reading the AttnFlags but
having to 
> change your program when a new version of the OS came out.

Well, we don't know if that's going to be a no-no.  As somebody
pointed out, you aren't supposed to open exec.library as a
library...you're supposed to peek it because it has a static address
in memory ($4).  And the 68060.library changes the AttnFlag, it's
documented in the developer info for 68060 on aminet by phase5 (I
forgot the file name).

