@NODE "Mail_526" "Re: Quest"
From: Toby Zuijdveld <hotcakes@abacus.net.au>
	Blitz List <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Date: Sat, 26 Dec 1998 11:42:50 +0500
Organization: =?iso-8859-1?Q?Res=A1stance?=
Subject: Re: Quest
Encoding: quoted-printable

On 24-Dec-98, amorel set out across the seas with this message:

->orso. But that isnt foolproof. Is there a better way to recognise a

The safest way is to look at the following offsets into the file, and che=
ck to
see if they equal the thingymawatsit that I typed next to it =3D]

$438 =3D "M"
$43A =3D "K"

xxxTracker (ie Pro, Star, etc etc) modules have their four byte id at $43=
8. =

Standard headers for various versions are : "M.K.", "M K ", "M!K!", "    =
",
"FLT4"...  and probably a few others, too.  So checking for just M and K
wouldn't work for all tunes, but it *is* the safest way.

-- =


