Hi David

Thanks for the tips. Actually I have now found that the problem is not as
clear cut as I thought. I managed to compile and run two different source
codes last night, and create an executable. However this was not without
several crashes - like compile/run once - OK - do it again - crash. I haven't
been able to reproduce the empty-ted crash since last time I wrote.

So I'm a bit baffled because when it was crashing on an empty Ted I did it
repeatedly - so whatever was crashing it survived a soft reset? I dunno.

Anyway, I think its not a single cause. I'm going to check out changing the
debugger - before I got BSS I was using LESDebugger (they're the same
functionally but the BSS one runs separately to support multiple source files
- not something I'm likely to need a lot of) and you say you're using that,
also someone else mentioned a patch for RedDebug so I'll look into that.

I can only think that maybe my whole system had got messed up when I was
getting crashes on empty Ted and the fact that I have successfully compiled
and run and then got a crash on *subsequent* compilation does point a finger
of suspicion at the debugger - especially since it stays active after the first
compilation/run and so is in memory for the second compilation... 

> I've got a Blizzard 1260/50 and the only crashes I have are due to my programs
>:) Maybe there's some serious differences between the Blizzard and Apollo
>boards that Blitz doesn't like. Do you need the 68060.library with the Apollo
>boards? If so, do you have that installed. Have you tried changing Ted
>versions? I think the version I have is 2.24.

Yes it uses the 060.library (with a 040.library and a o4o.library too, yeah?)
and the docs say to install this before the board otherwise it might not even
boot. So yes, I have them. I'm using SuperTed from BSS. Going to swap debugger
first.

> The keyboard disable on the Blizzard is next to useless, as it disables the
>entire board, rather that being able to disable the 060 by itself. And on my

Yes, same on my previous 030 board. Although in the case of Simon the Sorcerer
I think a vanilla 1200 would be fine..

> I've found that only about 10% (or less) of my commercial games work now - a

Oh, cheer me up. This was my xmas pressie to me!

Actually Doom, AB3d2, Breathless etc. are all very nice.. Frontier plays nice
too, although I had my fill of that years back..

Cheers
Mike Child

PS. Any AB3d2 fans - I will be uploading a new 16 level game to aminet very 
soon.



