>>>> What exactly does 'good money' mean?
>>>  It was around =A31000, but it's too late now. We have an Assm progra=
mmer
>>>  who is working on it.

>> okay, now I can see how some Amiga companies can still make a profit
>> when they refer to "writing a 3D space combat engine for =A31000" as g=
ood
>> money. Maybe you should use a different term when advertizing jobs in
>> future ;)

> Well, adequate money would surely be more fitting :o) So using the term=
s
> here Foundation made you rich, right ? :o)

Not rich but I would consider it 'not bad' money ;) Sorry if I sounded a
little
'off' with my previous message but I don't like to see this kind of thing=

on the blitz-list. If someone is able to program a 3D engine and/or the
gameplay (AI) for a game I'd rather see them team up with some others
(or do it alone) where they would get MUCH bigger rewards. The blitz-list=

isn't a pool of talent that can be swayed with fake offers such as
'good money'. Perhaps a little more honesty would have made things
much clearer such as 'X amount payed in return of Y' or an even more
honest offer such as an honest share/percentage of profits which is the
accepted method as used by Pagan Software.

The current commercial Amiga games scene offers small rewards which
are often spread between many people. Retail taking big shares from the
distributers, distributers taking big shares from publishers, publishers
taking big shares from developers and so on. The last thing we need is
developers ripping off other developers! The only way to avoid this is
to be honest when offering out work. I'd also like to point out that
*anyone*
who can make a half decent product will get a publishing contract. Please=

consider this if you have a wish to work on a commercial product.

Cheers,

-- =

< Paul Burkey - http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk >



