@NODE "Mail_556" "Re: Reading CD ROM ID Numbers"
From: "BootBlock/Carnage" <BootBlock@Bigfoot.com>
Subject: Re: Reading CD ROM ID Numbers
Date: Wed, 30 Dec 1998 01:18:32 -0000
	charset="Windows-1252"
Encoding: 7bit

Jonas Thorell wrote:

>Rick Hodger (rick.thehub@bigfoot.com) wrote:
>
>>> While on the subject of CD ROM's, could someone tell me how to read
>>>the (C)Copyright/Producer/etc info on CD's?
>
>>They aren't on the CD, those are gotten from a CDID file stored on
>>your hard-disk.  CD's do *not* contain any information about their
>>contents other than a standard Table of Contents which just contains
>>data like the offsets of the tracks, nos of tracks etc.

All that CD ID files contain is the CD title, artist and the name of the
tracks. (I've done me own CD player (Trinity Player)). Actually, I'm
thinking of a way that CD ID file's comment field could be used too....

>What's the purpose of entering something in those fields in MakeCD then?
>Besides, a utility program shipped with AsimCDFS can show what software
>was used to make the CD in the first place. Somehow I doubt that it was
>automagically transfered to my harddrive the same instant...

Yeah, when creating (audio) CD's, you enter the Producer, Artist,
Creation Date, CD Code, etc into the burning software and it sticks it on
the CD. But I just don't know how to access this info!

Anyway, here's how you get a CD's ID number:

TOCCDID$="ID"+Right$("0000"+Str$(TotalTracksOnCD.b),2)+Right$(Hex$(LengthOfT
rack2.l),6)+Right$(Hex$(AddressOfLastTrack.l),6)

(all on one line)

