@NODE "Mail_559" "Re: Reading CD ROM ID Numbers"
From: "BootBlock/Carnage" <BootBlock@Bigfoot.com>
Subject: Re: Reading CD ROM ID Numbers
Date: Wed, 30 Dec 1998 20:38:30 -0000
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 8bit


Mikkel L°kke wrote:

> Anyway, here's how you get a CD's ID number:
>
TOCCDID$="ID"+Right$("0000"+Str$(TotalTracksOnCD.b),2)+Right$(Hex$(LengthOfT
> rack2.l),6)+Right$(Hex$(AddressOfLastTrack.l),6)

>Erm, this doesn't give a unique number each time.

It's extremely rare that two CDs ever have the same ID number. They both
would have to have tracks that were all exactly the same length up until the
very last track, as the address of the last track would have be in the same
position on the CD. (say, 62 mins into the CD)

> I mean a copied CD would
>have the same ID as the original, right ?

Yup. They would have to be copied exactly (pregaps, no silence cut-offs,
etc).

>Well, some PC games can only be
>played from the CD that installed them. How is this possible ?


So if you installed a game from the original CD and then inserted the copied
CD when it asked for it (when running the game), it would reject it?
Hmmm.... the only thing I can think of is that it checks the creation date
on the CD, as I think most CD burning software puts the current date in the
date field.
--
