@NODE "Mail_583" "save IFF sample"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Thu, 03 Dec 1998 06:27:26 -0500
Subject: save IFF sample

Warning: This is a message in MIME format. Your mail reader does not
support MIME. Some parts of this message will be readable as plain text.
To see the rest, you will need to upgrade your mail reader.


--BOUNDARY.1748361104.1

Hi Everybody,

Blitz has all sorts of commands for creating, playing, and modifying sound
samples.
But no command to save a sample to disk.

So, I came up with the attached function to save a sample as a standard
IFF/8SVX sound sample.  It seems to work properly.

The problem I have is that I don't quite understand how the "loop" part
works.
(The routine now just ignores any loop information).
Does anybody know how to get the loop info and save it too?

The other reason I'm posting this is that maybe Fred or one of you other ASM
coders might want to include this as a command in one of your libraries.

I am "ASM-challenged" myself.

Translation:  I'm too dumb to code ASM  ;)

Later...
-- 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748361104.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="savesamp.asc"
Encoding: quoted-printable


; Save a loaded sample as standard iff/8svx sample
; Curt Esser  <camge@ix.netcom.com>
; pd - use in any way you like
; but please send me a copy of any improvements
; last modified  Dec 02 1998


;The first 12 bytes of an IFF file are used to distinguish between an Ami=
ga
;picture (FORM-ILBM), an Amiga sound sample (FORM-8SVX), or other file
;conforming to the IFF specification.  The middle 4 bytes is the count of=

;bytes that follow the "FORM" and byte count longwords.  (Numbers are sto=
red
;in M68000 form, high order byte first.)

;FutureSound audio file, 15000 samples at 10.000KHz, file is 15048 bytes =
long.

;0000: 464F524D 00003AC0 38535658 56484452    FORM..:.8SVXVHDR
;      F O R M     15040 8 S V X  V H D R

;0010: 00000014 00003A98 00000000 00000000    ......:.........
;            20    15000        0        0

;0020: 27100100 00010000 424F4459 00003A98    '.......BODY..:.
;     10000 1 0    1.0   B O D Y     15000

;0000000..03 =3D "FORM", identifies this as an IFF format file.
;FORM+00..03 (ULONG) =3D number of bytes that follow.  (Unsigned long int=
=2E)
;FORM+03..07 =3D "8SVX", identifies this as an 8-bit sampled voice.

;????+00..03 =3D "VHDR", Voice8Header, describes the parameters for the B=
ODY.
;VHDR+00..03 (ULONG) =3D number of bytes to follow.
;VHDR+04..07 (ULONG) =3D samples in the high octave 1-shot part.
;VHDR+08..0B (ULONG) =3D samples in the high octave repeat part.
;VHDR+0C..0F (ULONG) =3D samples per cycle in high octave (if repeating),=
 else 0.
;VHDR+10..11 (UWORD) =3D samples per second.  (Unsigned 16-bit quantity.)=

;VHDR+12     (UBYTE) =3D number of octaves of waveforms in sample.
;VHDR+13     (UBYTE) =3D data compression (0=3Dnone, 1=3DFibonacci-delta =
encoding).
;VHDR+14..17 (FIXED) =3D volume.  (The number 65536 means 1.0 or full vol=
ume.)

;????+00..03 =3D "BODY", identifies the start of the audio data.
;BODY+00..03 (ULONG) =3D number of bytes to follow.
;BODY+04..NNNNN      =3D Data, signed bytes, from -128 to +127.

;=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D

; Call it with the sample # to save, and the full save path $tring

; returns -1 (True) sucess
;          0 (False) sample doesn't exist
;          1 disk error - save unsuccesful  :(

Function.b SaveSample{samplenumber.w,saveIFF$}

If Peek.l(Addr Sound(samplenumber))            ;make sure there's a sampl=
e loaded!

  sndstart.l=3DPeek.l(Addr Sound(samplenumber))  ;the start of the sample=
 data

  slen.l=3D(Peek.w(Addr Sound (samplenumber)+6) AND $FFFF)*2  ;data  leng=
th in bytes

  tlen.l=3Dslen+40  ;total file length less 8 bytes for "FORM" + length

  per.l=3D(Peek.w(Addr Sound(samplenumber)+4) AND $FFFF)  ;the sample per=
iod

  persec.w=3D 3579440/per    ;the actual frequency for the IFF header

Else
  Function Return 0        ;sorry, that sample doesn't exist!
EndIf

; -- OK, we have the needed info - now let's save it to disk

If WriteFile (0,saveIFF$)  ;attempt to create the disk file
  error=3D-1
  FileOutput 0
  Print "FORM"             ;start of the IFF header
  WriteMem 0,&tlen,4       ;total bytes following the header
  Print "8SVXVHDR"         ;8svx sample ID, and start of Voice Header
  temp.l=3D20
  WriteMem 0,&temp,4       ;bytes in Voice Header chunk
  WriteMem 0,&slen,4       ;data bytes in 1 shot part
  temp.l=3D0
  WriteMem 0,&temp,4       ;for looping (0 for no loop)
  WriteMem 0,&temp,4       ;"     "     "
  WriteMem 0,&persec,2     ;frequency of the sample
  tempb.b=3D1
  WriteMem 0,&tempb,1      ;octaves
  WriteMem 0,&temp,1       ;compression (0=3Dnot compressed)
  temp.l=3D1                 ;volume (full volume)
  WriteMem 0,&temp,4
  Print "BODY"             ;start of Body chunk
  WriteMem 0,&slen,4       ;bytes of actual sample data
  WriteMem 0,sndstart,slen ;OK, finally!  Write the data
  CloseFile 0
  Use Window 0
Else
  error=3D1
EndIf

Function Return error

End Function

--BOUNDARY.1748361104.1--




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_584" "Re: save IFF sample"
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <FlameDuck@usa.net>
Date: Fri, 04 Dec 1998 02:03:19 +0200
Organization: A97
Subject: Re: save IFF sample
Encoding: quoted-printable
