@NODE "Mail_648" "Re: Variables"
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <FlameDuck@usa.net>
Date: Wed, 09 Dec 1998 12:11:30 +0200
Organization: A97
Subject: Re: Variables
Encoding: quoted-printable
X-Info: mailto:sf@xxl.ots.dk in case of problems!

Hello Toby.

On 09-Dec-98, Toby Zuijdveld wrote:
> On 09-Dec-98, Mikkel L=F8kke set out across the seas with this message:=


> ->point in using the even command if you declare any byte types, as the=

> ->memory will then again be offsat on an odd byte, and you will have to=

> ->insert a pading byte afterwards.

> Hmm?  Isn't that what the #Even# command is supposed to prevent?  ;]

No. The Even command makes sure that the NEXT Dc is on an even address. N=
ow
if your structure looks like :

BlahBlah1 dc.b 0
BlahBlah2 dc.l 1

Then BlahBlah2 (which is a longword, obviously) will have been offset by =
a
byte (BlahBlah1) so it is now on an odd address, causing a significant
slowdown, or a GURU on 68000/68010.


Regards
-- =

