@NODE "Mail_652" "Re: Vertical ScanRates"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Tue, 1 Dec 1998 22:12:42 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Date: Tue, 01 Dec 1998 22:08:45 +0000
Subject: Re: Vertical ScanRates

Hi,

> I'm trying to figure out the FramesPerSecond my game currently runs at.

Simple, let your game run for 1000 frames, then check how many
seconds have passed. It should be easy to work out the fps from
this point eg, 1000/secondspassed = fps

> However, I'm unsure whether I check to see if the Timer is >49 (=50) or
> greater than the vertical scanrate of te display.

I doubt you have any great need to calculate the fps value every
frame. It should be possible but is it really needed?

> Obviously PAL modes all have a VSR of 50, and that's what I started
> using, however, my cybergraphics screen modes have vertical rates
> of 67 and 70 etc.

This has nothing to do with frames per second though, has it? For
example, a game running at 50fps on a cybergfx screen would also
run at 50fps on an NTSC screen.

> Now would I always check to see if the timer is >50 or >VSR of the
> screenmode?

This might be found in the DisplayInfo for the ModeID which can be
read with the GetDisplayInfoData_() function. You'd have to read
the autodocs on the DisplayInfo structures. I don't see a real reason
to need this info in a game though.

> I know all AGA modes have fixed rates but you can change all of this
> when you define a new CyberGraphX mode, which is why everyone
> has different ModeID's for the same screenmode.

I think you might be trying to do something that is much harder than
it needs to be. Can you explain why the VSR would be usefull for
your problem?

Cheers,

-- 
< Paul Burkey - http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk >

"Some herbert's touching up yer bird."
-- Brass Eye




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_653" "Re: VWait"
          with SMTP id <19981216231703.CILC10635@ameritech.net>
          for <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>; Wed, 16 Dec 1998 17:17:03 -0600
From: pkocourek@ameritech.net (Paul Kocourek)
Date: Wed, 16 Dec 1998 17:14:09
Subject: Re: VWait
Organization: None (sh82)
X-Receipt: No
X-Form: Standard.FORM

> On Wed, 16 Dec 1998 22:07:25 +0200 you wrote:

> Hello Daniel.
> 
> On 16-Dec-98, Daniel Allsopp wrote:
> 
> > Is it logical/sensible to put a VWait into a gfxcard
display?
> If I run my
> > game under cybergraphX I get about 100fps in Lowres but
if
> I put a VWait
> in
> > it takes the fps to 50, the scrolling and speed of the
game
> doesn't
> change
> > however.
> 
> Sounds strange, but under no circumstances should you use
VWait.
> You should
> use WaitTOF_ instead.
> 
> > What I'm asking, is do I need a VWait in my code for
WPA8_
> 'ing to a
> > window?
> 
> I have no idea. I would however do it to be on the safe
side.
> 
> 
> Regards
>

As long as it does not interfere with frame rates and program
functions, by all means put a delay of some sort in.  Keep
in mind that down the road, the Amiga computers of the future
may have multiple speeds of processors in the market much
like the PC market does i.e. 486 (at many Mhz variations),
Pentium 60/75/90/100/etc, Pentium II 266/300/etc.  Regardless
of which chip/speed future Amigas use, a delay of some sort,
such as the system-friendly " Delay_(1)" will allow a given
program/game to run at a specific guaranteed speed, and not
too fast.  For example, there is a shareware Amiga version
of the old "Defender" arcade program.  On a stock A500/A2000,
it ran just fine.  On my A1200/030/50Mhz machine (admittedly
already slow by what is available out there now), the Amiga
"Defender" runs so fast, it is utterly unplayable.  The missiles
all shoot down and nuke your cities almost the moment you
press the key to go.

Using Delay_(1) forces the machine to delay 1/60th of a second
every time through the loop, so that no matter how fast a
processor you have, the game will run at its intended speed.

Merry Christmas to all you Blitzers.


--



@ENDNODE
