@NODE "Mail_656" "Re: VWait"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sat, 19 Dec 1998 18:20:09 -0500
Subject: Re: VWait

Hi,

On 16-Dec-98, Paul Kocourek wrote:
`
>> Sounds strange, but under no circumstances should you use
> VWait.
>> You should
>> use WaitTOF_ instead.

Is there a problem with the Vwait command?  I have tried both ways and
found
no noticable difference either way.

Does Vwait hog the processor like MouseWait?  Not that it means much, but
the manual doesn't warn about Vwait like it does about MouseWait.

> Using Delay_(1) forces the machine to delay 1/60th of a second
> every time through the loop, so that no matter how fast a
> processor you have, the game will run at its intended speed.

Er, not exactly.  For example, if the intended program speed was 1/50th
second per loop (or 1/60th in NTSC), adding a Delay_(1) would now cause the
program to run at half speed on the slower machine (1/50th for the main
loop, then another 1/50th waiting time)

If the intended program speed is 1/50 th, then simply doing a WaitTOF_ (or
Vwait) at the top of each loop will make sure that it never runs any faster
than 1/50th no matter what the processor speed.

If the intended speed is less than 1/50th, for example 1/25th (or 2 TOF's
per loop)
you can add a counter with a Vblank interrupt, or use ResetTimer and Ticks
to make sure that 2 TOF's have passed before starting the next loop, to
keep faster machines in line.

Simply adding a Delay_ each loop will only make the loop run slower on ALL
machines, but the program can still run faster on faster machines.
So maybe now you would need 3 TOF's to complete the loop on a slow machine,
and only 2 or 1 on a fast system...

Later...
-- 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
