@NODE "Mail_673" "Re: Would YOU like a new Blitz Compiler?"
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <FlameDuck@usa.net>
Date: Wed, 02 Dec 1998 03:33:48 +0200
Organization: A97
Subject: Re: Would YOU like a new Blitz Compiler?
Encoding: quoted-printable
X-Info: mailto:sf@xxl.ots.dk in case of problems!

Hello Matthew.

On 30-Nov-98, Matthew Parsons wrote:

> It seems that only Frederic can  be bothered to make a new compiler,
> but (And I don't blame him) he wants to use his own command set. Also
> he seems to have based it around 68000 ASM!!!!!

Strange. I wonder if this is based on the presumtion that this is what
AMiGA's use.

> So now I'm a little irritated, so much so that I've started coding my
> own Compiler.

> My main goal was to make a CPU independant compiler, this is so that
> the system is as future proof as possible.

Nothing is future proof.

> Well Here it is:

>                         Blitz Basic 2 Upgrade

> This is a small document covering my new Blitz basic compiler format.
> I have decided to make my own Blitz Basic compatable compiler, this is =
my
> first compiler for a programming language which I did not design. =


> With this I want to try to tell you how my compiler works, and hopefull=
y =

> you will be able to help me improve and add to it.

> I will firstly list my goals:

> 1. Make a Blitz Basic 2 Source Code compatable compiler.
> 2. Make it CPU independant.
> 3. Make it future proof.
> 4. Allow easy Third Party Expasion.


> The first goal is obvious, and needs no explaination.

You know offcourse that the original Blitz Basic 2 is heavily based arrou=
nd
the cuurent AMiGA hardware...

> Ok, I had better explain how goal 2 is realised. I have decided on the =

> bilayer compiler system. This is where the Blitz commands are compiled =
> an intermediate code, then the intermediate code is compiled to the
target
> CPU's asm.

Nice, but this would certainly not result in fast code.

> But I have a long established hatred of C so I will use my own
intermediate
> code. I have dicided to call my intermediate code PsudoASM (not a
spelling

> mistake). So we now have this situation:

>        BLITZ---->PsudoASM
> PsudoASM---->ASM (68K or PPC)
>          ASM---->Machine Code

Call me stupid, but why not just write a Blitz compiler for it ? It seems=

be quite stupid to first compile it to "psudo ASM", and THEN real
MachineCode. Also there is no difference between ASM and Machine Code,
except one is Numbers, one is Mnenomics.

> I will try to make PsudoASM as close to PPC Asm as possible, this is wi=
ll
> result in the 68K version being less efficient than it could be, but th=
is
> will still be better than the original compiler. I have decided to do i=
t =

> this way because the PPC is a fairly typical RISC machine and all futur=
e
> CPU's will be RISC.

Really ? How far in the future are we speaking about ? 3-4 years is hardl=
y
the future.

> The compiler outputs ASM source file that is ready to be assembled usin=
g =

> a standard public domain assembler.

Why not just do it on the fly ? It can be done with a look-up table.

> If you can improved or help in the implementation of this design then =

> please contact me at:

> billyray@enterprise.net

Hrmmm, I was close.

> On a final note, I think Blitz Mode should be removed. Well, maybe we
> should keep it until we have a PPC version of the OS. A Blitz mode game=

> would run on a PPC quite happily, but an amiga mode version would be
doing
> lots of context switches, this means a slow down.

Funny, you just contradicted your first objective. (The Blitz Compatibili=
ty
Thingy)

Not that I want to bash anyone, but I think that Frederic's way of doing
(Lib based, with optimised ASM libraries) is great ! And very "Future
proof" indeed.


Regards
-- =

